commit_message:
Fix migration downgrade 147 with mysql

Determine each service's availability zone and re-insert it back into the
database to undo migration 147 with mysql.

Fixes bug 1207309

Change-Id: I6a96215f9e97874a64f9bcef56c3d32747fb754c

commit_message:
Make pki_setup work with OpenSSL 0.9.x

Support for "default" in default_md was only added
in "recent" OpenSSL versions. Use sha1 (which is what
"default" maps to anyway) for older openssl versions.

Also sync the generated openssl config file with
the defaults from OpenSSL 1.0 and newer.

Fixes: LP Bug #1209249
Change-Id: I4ba79dbfdfc2df81cfb0f1edde23d3fbc1384637

commit_message:
Remove nova_volume

nova_volume has been depreciated, in favour of cinder.

Now that we are working on the Havana branch,
it seems like an appropriate time to remove it.

Change-Id: Ief063f92a719f950507d2ad8e21eb2cc44691bd0

commit_message:
Force $DEST to have wider permissions

This is particularly useful in the case where we create the
home directory above and the permissions are too strict.

Other users, such as the apache user, need read/execute for this
directory.

Change-Id: I908d993dbcd863b482030afcc04e5e7b9f4cffa1

Drop extra credential indexes

For mysql ForeignKey constraints were removed but the fields stayed as indexes.
This migration drops them.

bp db-sync-models-with-migrations

'}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2013-08-08 10:54:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Ben,

There's some extensions which are not ported to V3 such as fping, cloudpipe, floating_ips etc which probably aren't worth copying over. Some of that functionality should be accessed directly to the relevant service (eg neutron). I think I read somewhere there was a goal of making novaclient the universal access point for openstack services? I'm not sure about that, but if its true, a call direct to those services would have to be added to novaclient, but its probably so different that its not worth copying over the v2 version.

I think there are going to be some cases where the v2 version just works or is very close to what is required, so the v3 file might be able to just inherit from v2 rather than duplicating the code. 

In other cases I think the technique of copying in one changeset and the modifying in another is good. 

One suggestion I have though is not to copy them all at once, but start with a very small (as small as you get that is vaguely useful) subset of novaclient functionality to implement for v3. And then slowly port from v2 (perhaps a command at a time) to v3. I think that will make it much easier for reviewers."}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2013-08-09 15:49:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-08-09 17:08:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Begin adding v3 api support

Create the v3 directory and populate it with some of the basic
files from v2 that will be needed.  These files are straight
copies so that v3-specific changes will be easier to see in
subsequent changes.

Extensions will be added individually in future changes.

bp v3-api

Change-Id: I9538c70ccc6fb001ce2fd43ccfd41870f247c67e

commit_message:
Bug fix pyparsing upgrade for python quantum client

The python-quantumclient package may not include the correct
version of pyparsing in its dependencies, requiring us to
ensure that it is upgraded to the latest version prior to
usage

Change-Id: Id0064596ec277fe5d54441ab316ee146acc75f5f

Isn't there some more DRY way to do this, perhaps by introducing an external function or mixin?"}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2013-07-31 15:22:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

So there are 2 reasons I did it this way:

1. While the base test case does get imported the way that credentials and clients get setup is a bit different in scenario. To be able to reuse the get_isolated cred methods would require more changes to class an inheritance structure of the tests here then I thought was needed for a change of this scope.

2. The scenario tests use the official python clients. So the _get_isolated_cred() I added here uses python-keystoneclient instead of the tempest keystone client. I figured it was better to do it this way to ensure consist use of the official clients vs tempest clients.

I think because of the second reason we should keep 2 copies of get_isolated_creds lying around. But, the bigger question is whether we keep it this way and the other get_isolated_creds in classmethods for the test classes or put them somewhere else like in tempest.common?'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-07-31 15:38:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I guess I'm ok with this given your reasons. But let's make sure we don't end up with a third copy. I think you should put comments at the top of both methods warning about the other copy in case some one makes a change to fix some issue."}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2013-07-31 18:19:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-31 19:10:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Works for me

[{'created': '2013-07-29 15:26:06.000000000', 'message': 'Add locking for adding a ssh security group rule

This commit adds locking to the scenario tests that create a new
security group rule to allow ssh on the default security group. You
can only add the same rule once to a security group and when running
tempest in parallel this will cause a possible error.

Part of blueprint speed-up-tempest

Change-Id: Icaffd0c40f55d94014ab4758b392bf5c38f0b0f6
'}, {'created': '2013-07-30 15:56:10.000000000', 'message': "Add tenant isolation for scenario tests

Currently the scenario tests have a race condition between tests
that create a new security group rule to allow ssh on the default
security group. A security group rule can only be added the same
to security group once and when running tempest in parallel this
will cause a possible error because the scenario tests where running
in the same tenant an have the same default security group. This
commit fixes this by adding tenant isolation to the scenario tests
so that each scenario test will have it's own tenant and thus it's
own default security group.

commit_message:
Add tenant isolation for scenario tests

Currently the scenario tests have a race condition between tests
that create a new security group rule to allow ssh on the default
security group. A security group rule can only be added to the same
security group once and when running tempest in parallel this
will cause a possible error because the scenario tests were running
in the same tenant which have the same default security group. This
commit fixes this by adding tenant isolation to the scenario tests
so that each scenario test will have it's own tenant and thus it's
own default security group.

To add tenant isolation for the scenario tests and use the official
python clients without duplicating code the isolated_credential code
was broken out as a separate class in a new file in tempest/common.
This class will either use the tempest identity client or
python-keystone client depending on whether it for an api test or a
scenario test.

Part of blueprint speed-up-tempest

Change-Id: Icaffd0c40f55d94014ab4758b392bf5c38f0b0f6

commit_message:
Switch use of select() to poll()

This commit switches the use of select() in ssh.py to use poll()
instead. Using select() does not work with large FD numbers, but
by switching to poll() such constraints don't exist.

Change-Id: I8c4dd22b86e5a570691e35e2390c3679371ae1eb

commit_message:
Add syslog logging to quantum-ha-tool

Add syslog logging to quantum-ha-tool and direct
any output from the command to /dev/null so we do
not generate output to cron

Change-Id: I225dd90252a4a54b4bdab05a98068ca4e06903f0

commit_message:
Fix get_available_resource docstrings

libvirt's get_available_resource docstring had incorrect information,
this patch corrects it and clarifies the base, xenapi, and vmware docstrings as
well. Other drivers don't have long docstrings with the same issue.

Part of bp no-compute-fanout-to-scheduler

Change-Id: Iac943a7fa70337fbb0f742553a0e064511f0c265

commit_message:
bug fix restart quantum-plugin-openvswitch-agent

In the cookbook-openstack-network/recipes/common.rb, for "openvswitch",
it restarts the service quantum-plugin-openvswitch-agent whether or not
that service is running.  The service would only be running if the openvswitch
recipe was also included.

Fixes: Bug #1210400
Implements: make the restart quantum-plugin-openvswitch-agent conditional

Change-Id: I8801450ac88547e5961bb37f0d1b7c002671c9e8

commit_message:
Configurable network labels used for showing IPs in instance details

The ip shown in the instance detail was hard coded to be obtained from
a nova netwok label 'private' or 'usenet'. With this change, the labels
is configurable based on a regex pattern.

Fixes bug 1206303

Change-Id: I73d896e6b85bdebe342a777219b9b60d6954f8b6

commit_message:
Raise warlock requirement

Glance PATCH API need use new 'require' condition for schema to validate
income requests.

Raise warlock requirement to >=1.0.1,<2 as older warlock requires a too
old jsonschema to be useful.

See bug #1202391 for details.

Change-Id: I0ac148850a5b1254bf0827c7de2db1464a6703d8
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Add support for the Nexus 1000V into the Cisco Plugin.

This will enable the Cisco Nexus 1000V to integrate with the Cisco plugin
and be used to drive the realization of Neutron constructs.
Network profile and Policy profile are introduced as extended neutron
resources, while n1kv:profile_id is introduced as an extended attribute
for network and port objects. Necessary changes to the Cisco plugin are
made to accomodate Nexus 1000V as a configurable vswitch plugin.

Implements: blueprint cisco-plugin-n1k-support
Change-Id: I951e10c57d74c935fca8754c0e21e1ac9df35704

commit_message:
Interpolate strings after calling _()

The original uninterpolated string is the key used to lookup translations,
so it's necessary to interpolate strings *after* calling into gettext.
Otherwise, the strings won't be translated correctly
This will ensure the string gets looked up by gettext correctly

Change-Id: I1a529bbc1e9ef6ee79502a66f68bc793d2e23b94

commit_message:
Progress config reference for networking

This update structures and fleshes various sections of the
configuration reference for networking and misc other changes,
including:

* making a new section for RPC as related to networking
* splitting out plugin tables into a separate file
* sectionin out tables for other sections
* adding zeromq to the RPC section for compute

patchset2/3: fixes whitespace

patchset4 fixes based on review -thanks!

Change-Id: Ic2dc88118f5057c985bfe4cf5671ac9c9f8b2c6e
bp:restructure-documentation

commit_message:
Always close HTTP connections in the container updater.

This is needed on Pythons (e.g. PyPy) which do not use reference
counting.

Change-Id: Ib75a2e63bdd6b6bc726fb3dbf905d36f427aaf2f

commit_message:
Handle None value properties in glance-replicator

bug 1208417

In glance-replicator, all image properties in the master glance are
synced to the slave. But there are circumstances(kernel_id or
ramdisk_id, etc.) when image properties in the master are None.
glance-relicator doesn't handle this issue, thus all such properties
are trasnlated to the string 'None' in the slave glance, which is
incorrect.

This patch fixes this problem by add a check before post metadata to
the slave glance. All None properties are translated to '' before
posted to slave glance.

Change-Id: I9b674db907f707ac4dce28c8a7e3d81fcce61193

commit_message:
Update network configuration for overclouds.

The overcloud network configuration was not migrating ip addresses and
ports onto the exterior integration bridge. This is fine when the
bridge is not the default route, and/or is on a different interface,
but behaves very poorly when only a single interface is present. Since
we don't use br-ex in undercloud setups (today), and don't use
br-ctlplane in overcloud setups, we can use the same code for
migrating address and routes by updating our configuration instead.

Change-Id: I85a455bd2b03089bf39c34a3b69af78af09ce286

commit_message:
Set a bridge id for external bridges.

Unlike br-int we were not setting a bridge-id. I'm not sure if it's
needed, but it is consistent to add one, and will allow consolidating
other code which currently differs only by setting such an id.

Change-Id: I0e5ada816948cc7fd3a5fe7b5b92b7bb89ebaf5a

remove Brick deps on cinder.exception

This patch removes more cinder.exception
dependencies from brick.  This involves
moving some exceptions into brick's
exception module.

commit_message:
Setup ovs bridges before we start services.

The ovs bridges need to be setup before we start any neutron services
that depend on them. The right way to do that is to set them up during
configure, and start services in post-configure.

Change-Id: I316e0d4a9e71479ea2e9ae338d243b4cec5391b8

commit_message:
Remove in-instance network policy configuration.

Network policy should be driven by API clients rather than in-instance
scripts, as using Heat to proxy the handover just adds an unnecessary
layer of indirection. We need to keep the logic for configuring ovs
within instances, just not the neutron net-create etc.

Change-Id: Iaee70ef5c9d1ff2a608e4ea64e766920bfba7f42

commit_message:
Remove Brick iser dependency on cinder

This patch removes the brick iser.py's dependency
on cinder exceptions and volume_utils.
This required moving some exceptions out of cinder's
exception.py that the iser.py raises.  Also had
to create a BrickException and refactor existing
brick exceptions to use the new BrickException model.

Fixes Bug #1210312

Change-Id: I672375807fed4952e5321fbcd9b57b9ef369f68f

commit_message:
Permit using different libvirt hypervisors.

Folk will want to deploy lxc/qemu etc overclouds. The libvirt type
needs to be controllable for this, independent of software
installation.

Change-Id: I29e5fea72f9cb983576410baa8f50ab060c08fe3

commit_message:
Setup new cloud neutron config via APIs.

The network configuration within a cloud is global configuration, not
per-instance configuration : heat metadata is the wrong vehicle for
expressing it, as heat would result in multiple network nodes trying
to apply the same change (for instance).

Change-Id: Ifee7183aca4b18ae412eaa5f97ad6680dbaa291a

commit_message:
Set a physical bridge for network nodes.

The overcloud control plane needs to bring up an ovs bridge for the
ovs plugin hot-plugging and floating ip logic to work. The previous
in-instance script didn't migrate IP address and route information. We
can do that by using the core ovs script we wrote for baremetal setups
- triggered by setting the physical interface parameter.

Change-Id: I6d6b09140ee751371607c0963dc76cc5b95f7674

commit_message:
Remove unused network configuration metadata.

This is supplied to neutron etc via API calls - having it in Heat
leads to having redundancy, confusion and tricky scripts. Incubator
now has scripts to configure this and instances won't consult these
keys.

Change-Id: Ia45d9bf5bb326ec88f9f4a48c5520570cf5b6d72

commit_message:
Move glance image service client from nova and cinder into ironic

Most of the code was present on nova.image.glance and cinder.image.glance.

Should be removed once common code lands on python-glanceclient.

Changes to code in glanceclient:
   - import names
   - added import_versioned_module func. to image_service
   - register options when module ironic.common.image_service loaded

Change-Id: Ia7deb1a79c388333410b6abc24736481d435de77
Implements: blueprint image-tools

Fixes: bug 1207115

commit_message:
Fixes unique constraint regex

This patch fixes the regex being used to extract the marker from the
unique index error. The issue was caused because we introduced project
to the queue_marker index and it wasn't being considered in that regex.

This regex is more general. It matches the index name and gets the
marker from the end of the error message.

Change-Id: I02bc153636f10bc49b8634fc4bfeb4bf2b6d6597
Closes-bug: #1211386

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-12 18:45:49.000000000', 'message': 'fix(storage/mongo): unclaimed messages not listed

Adds a unit test that reproduces this error and applies the fix.

The fix is subtle. When messages are unclaimed, their claim expiration
time and claim ID are set to 0 and None respectively. The cause for
the bug is that claim expiration time is set to 0, rather than a valid
datetime object. As a result, the comparison silently fails.

The fix: fast-forward the expiration time of a claim to now.

Change-Id: I7781795c394b2a471012e072a522ee228d56a894
Closes-Bug: #1210633
'}, {'created': '2013-08-12 19:45:31.000000000', 'message': 'fix(storage/mongo): unclaimed messages not listed

Adds a unit test that reproduces this error and applies the fix.

The fix is subtle. When messages are unclaimed, their claim expiration
time and claim ID are set to 0 and None respectively. The cause for
the bug is that claim expiration time is set to 0, rather than a valid
datetime object. As a result, the comparison silently fails.

The fix: fast-forward the expiration time of a claim to now.

Change-Id: I7781795c394b2a471012e072a522ee228d56a894

commit_message:
fix(storage/mongo): unclaimed messages not listed

Adds a unit test that reproduces this error and applies the fix.

The fix is subtle. When messages are unclaimed, their claim expiration
time and claim ID are set to 0 and None respectively. The cause for
the bug is that claim expiration time is set to 0, rather than a valid
datetime object. As a result, the comparison silently fails.

The fix: fast-forward the expiration time of a claim to now.

Change-Id: I7781795c394b2a471012e072a522ee228d56a894
Closes-Bug: #1210633

commit_message:
doc(validation): update the sample config file

This patch add the configuration variables of transport driver-
specific limits and input validation to the sample config file,
so that the users don't need to open the source code to figure
out how to change the limits :)

Change-Id: I811b7dc4ca44d25a3cdb5402e11d599aa532ab39

commit_message:
User quota update should not exceed project quota

Move the default user quota setting code from db to quota.py,
because it is necessary to check if user quota is set in db
to get the settable quota for the user under a project.

Fixes bug 1208400

Change-Id: I83a4a7fcd8bf80b20e4e700bad7dd31294f8ed0b

commit_message:
More Python package fixes

* Add tools/fixup_stuff.sh to fix prettytable and httplib2 install
  with pip 1.4+
* Cache downloads properly in tools/install_pip.sh

Change-Id: I482590cb91f7a10c1436bc9015afd572ac1cc73e

commit_message:
Move resource usage sync functions to db backend

Resource usage sync functions was declared in cinder/quota.py, and
using db.api public methods. This functions was moved to database
backend implementation, so now sync functions can use private
methods of database backend, and session attribute can be removed
from this public methods.

Blueprint: db-session-cleanup

Change-Id: If5386e3dc1e0d6e3127732aeb5b35bbd96bc93f0

commit_message:
Sync models with migrations

This patch syncs models with migrations for:

-Endpoint
-CredentialModel
-TokenModel
-TrustModel

No actual schema change is taking place, this patch just corrects errors
in the model definitions.

Made class Index avaliable in keystone.common.sql.core

partially implements bp db-sync-models-with-migrations

Change-Id: I52f5c455360b65a2d5d884bbbec078dca6d34451

Added Backend API Database Implementation

Added a SQLite backed backend API implementation
that interfaces with the database using sqlalchemy.
All of the unit tests associated are included as
well.

commit_message:
MinDisk size based on the flavor's Disk size

When you create an instance from image  the instance disk size
is expanded to the disk size specified in the flavor.

Normally you cannot use the snapshot  for creating an instance
with smaller disk size (flavor)  because it  potentialy
causes a data corruption.

Every snapshots minDisk size should be inherited from the flavor.

bug 1200279

Change-Id: I1d0e909b78db2c863b4fbb54ad9065207f1a0abe

main controller

Related to blueprint nova-v3-api

commit_message:
Improve Neutron support in networking

New support in Neutron:
*neutron_url_timeout
*neutron_default_tenant_id
*neutron_ovs_bridge
*neutron_extension_sync_interval
*neutron_ca_certificates_file

Change-Id: Ia05c493c7f5ce93944ba73940b1d39d593e70952

to use list comprehensions in place of generators. This simplifies
some existing logic (e.g., retry handling) and sets us up nicely
for input validation. It should also be a little bit faster than
the previous approach, at the expense of increased memory usage.

commit_message:
Buffer message documents when enqueuing them, in lieu of streaming

This patch modifies the pipeline for the message post operation
to use list comprehensions in place of generators. This simplifies
some existing logic (e.g., retry handling) and sets us up nicely
for input validation. It should also be a little bit faster than
the previous approach, at the expense of increased memory usage.

Note that the SQLite driver was not modified (YAGNI).

Change-Id: Ia706dd7a3d71c57044d25a3c6e4e647dcb797240
Implements: blueprint buffer-messages

commit_message:
allows a mgmt user to migrate an instance to a specific host

a mgmt user and use the instance migrate api and specify a host that
they would like the instance to move to.
Fixing migration fake mode.

implements blueprint migration-force-to-host
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/reddwarf/+spec/migration-force-to-host

Change-Id: I1fd7b2f5ae5328de642ec1ad6ee4d62c5a29168f

commit_message:
Fix resource status in NEC Plugin

This commit makes sure that the plugin exposes right status in a
response body, and does not overwrite ERROR status until another
operation to the backend has succeeded.

This commit also changes NEC Plguin to use neutron constants instead of
OperationalStatus defined in this plugin.

Fixes: bug #1211319
Change-Id: Ic61b8e1b9d3f6c2be9567dd5a4606aa6d439c564

commit_message:
feat(validation): validate user input

The validation is implemented as a set of free-standing functions
in a separated module; each driver which uses storage functions
should call call the corresponding validation functions first.

Fixes: bug #1177971
Fixes: bug #1177976
Fixes: bug #1177979
Fixes: bug #1206175
Fixes: bug #1208873

Change-Id: I0b9c9766a9c3de42f2a2eb470cba0ab7265e669a

Thanks Nachi for taking a look.
1. What if l3-agent restarted? 
When it picks up the known routers - we have a hook there that will pick up the policy from the plugin and install it. I have some code that i am testing - will push it out soon.
2. What if l3-agent gets fwaas rpc call before the router is created? 
When the router is created - we can pick that up and handle it similar to (1)
3. What if fwaas resources deleted during l3-agent dies? 
No state is maintained on the Agent so i think we should be fine we always get it from the plugin.
4. What if driver failed to setup iptables?
We get an error while invoking the driver and this is propagated to the plugin - the FW will not go to ACTIVE state.'}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2013-07-10 18:45:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The general questions I have are:
1) does the agent enforce policies also on east-west traffic or is it just for north-south traffic?

2) It seems this agent 'extends' the l3 agent. When a new router is added to an agent, its namespace is created, and this ensures the firewall applies the rules only on the agent where the router is implemented.
Consider the following sequence of operations:

- Create router
   - Agent not invoked (router has no interfaces)
- Create firewall, policies, and stuff
   - Agent invoked - but has no effect since router namespace still not there
- add interface to router
   - l3 agent invoked, router namespace created, but firewall rules not applied

Is the above sequence correct? If yes, is there anything we should fix?"}, {'account_id': 6995, 'date': '2013-07-13 00:37:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 14.'}, {'account_id': 6995, 'date': '2013-07-13 00:51:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

Many Thanks Salvatore for the detailed review. I will pick up on the inline comments and fix them on the next patch. 

I am addressing ur comment (2) with patch 14 - this was something we were looking at and also brought up by Nachi in his review as well. 

Responses inline:

The general questions I have are: 

1) does the agent enforce policies also on east-west traffic or is it just for north-south traffic?

It is not East-West in that it will not be applied on vm instances in the same network within a tenant. If we go across networks within a tenant or across tenants - policies are enforced. And of course if we are going out to an external n/w it is applied. I hope that answers ur question.

2) It seems this agent 'extends' the l3 agent. When a new router is added to an agent, its namespace is created, and this ensures the firewall applies the rules only on the agent where the router is implemented. Consider the following sequence of operations:
- Create router
   - Agent not invoked (router has no interfaces)
- Create firewall, policies, and stuff
   - Agent invoked - but has no effect since router namespace still not there
- add interface to router
   - l3 agent invoked, router namespace created, but firewall rules not applied
Is the above sequence correct? If yes, is there anything we should fix?

U have hit the "nail on the head" :-). We were looking at this more from a restart scenario and this was also brought up by Nachi. I have addressed this with patch 14. When _router_added method is invoked in l3agent to handle namespaces, iptable rules etc - we insert ourselves in that path to get the policy from the FW plugin and apply it on to the driver. On agent side we are not maintaining any state. I will also update the doc with some details on this.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-13 01:26:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Works for me

commit_message:
Firewall as a Service (FWaaS) Agent

blueprint: quantum-fwaas-agent

This is the first iteration of the FWaaS Agent with some basic
functionality to enable integration of Plugin - Agent - Driver.

An inheritance approach is taken with the L3 Agent to enable the
agent side messaging.

Unit tests, included, coverage being increased

Change-Id: Ib0970fdc4ad1ac53df66fba172a5a7f7d7ee3f1b

commit_message:
Upgrade Scality driver to match minimum features

The Scality driver needs an upgrade to match minimum features:
- Havana: Clone Volume
- Icehouse: Extend Volume

Also, some features (Copy Image to Volume, Copy Volume to Image) already work but need automated tests.

Change-Id: Iac5ac2c58fd5ce62823f829a0a014decb4ad4958
Fixes: bug 1210240

commit_message:
validate modified files and build affected books

At the moment the validation script simply validates all
files and builds all books afterwards. This results in a
very long runtime (appr. 30 minutes at the moment).

With this patch only modified files are validated and only
affected books are built. A book is affected if one XML
file includes a modified file. If no book is directly
affected all books are built.

In this way, resources can be saved and validation is
performed much faster.

Change-Id: I17dcf119c0bafc4656c9f267f0d3f5ae884ea76e

commit_message:
Improvements in get_events SQL query perf

A few minor improvements to the SQL query generated
by the get_events call in the SQL storage driver:

* Don't use a subquery when no traits are being filtered
* Use ORDER BY on the query instead of doing sorting in
  Python
* Adds comments with documentation about the SQL that is
  generated from the queries so that the reader of the code
  understands the technique being used
* Fixes bug in filtering where t_datetime value was being
  checked for t_float trait filters

Change-Id: I59928aa8631b259aaaac3e0de26a13dae8e04b58
Closes-Bug: 1211291

commit_message:
Added plugin (e.g. memory) to monitor and collect data

This patch gives a plugin interface for users to add their own plugins to
monitor on compute nodes on the compute manager.

The compute manager loads the plugins and gets the metrics, and sends to
the scheduler for utilization based scheduling.
The patch also gives a sample to collect memory utilization data.

Change-Id: I4e827076f1c72f3b75b148b5f87da2520ae402cb

commit_message:
Remove external id -> internal uuid mapping

As agreed at meeting on 29 July 2013, the mapping between the external id
to the internal UUID is being removed. We are now going to use UUID-only
to keep the API consistent.

Change-Id: I683f927a86634292cacc4a58af4c19165e4df7fd

subject: Change swap_volume volume_api calls to use ID

commit_message:
Change swap_volume volume_api calls to use ID

Currently some volume_api calls in the swap_volume code pass a volume
dict rather than a volume ID. This patch fixes the issue. Also fix two
issues: (1) invalid reference to 'volume' which should be 'old_volume'
when passing arguments to VolumeUnattached argument prior to raising it
in the compute API, and (2) revert begin_detaching and reserve_volume
calls if swap_volume fails.

Change-Id: I9735ffbd1a4adc5250d41f837ad10bbf290cf193
Fixes: bug 1207356

commit_message:
Fix to allow ipv6 in host_ip for ESX/vSphere driver

Just needed to add '[' and ']' when creating urls.

Fixes LP# 1206595

Change-Id: I6b2cc86f9b0ff686ff6da794a469f6c9815933a1

commit_message:
Fix VMwareVCDriver to support multi-datastore

This fixes the issue of VCDriver selecting the first datastore of
Cluster while provisioning instances. User can provide a regex to
match with the desired datastores.

Fixes: bug #1104994

Change-Id: I319b0d8afd03e9fef00ea0c8c799790714685104

From the bugreport:
"I also want to point that "use = egg:swift#swift3" is wrongly stated in
the doc. It has to be "use = egg:swift3#swift3" - as swift3 is not a
module of swift but of swift3."

The above change is confirmed by
https://github.com/fujita/swift3/blob/master/README.md

Change-Id: Icc190cf01586f3d41faaf57a2771dc1af5883876
Closes-Bug: #1209254
'}]
commit_message:
Use egg:swift3#swift3 instead of egg:swift#swift3

From the bugreport:
"I also want to point that "use = egg:swift#swift3" is wrongly stated in
the doc. It has to be "use = egg:swift3#swift3" - as swift3 is not a
module of swift but of swift3."

The above change is confirmed by
https://github.com/fujita/swift3/blob/master/README.md

Change-Id: Icc190cf01586f3d41faaf57a2771dc1af5883876
Closes-Bug: #1209254

Change-Id: Iafce8e4a222677fc590bb579654e195dc4252a9e
'}]
commit_message:
Fail fast if Resource action methods are missing

If a resource is not actually a Resource with create(), delete() &c.
methods then something has gone horribly, horribly wrong. This is not a
priority for handling gracefully at runtime.

Change-Id: Iafce8e4a222677fc590bb579654e195dc4252a9e

commit_message:
Backport basic install guide fixes from trunk

From commit 7a06cb4:
 * Add missing prompts
 * Hide the quantum-ovs-cleanup listitem for ubuntu/debian
 * Fix apache error log path
 * Fix hostnames on network node
 * Fix mysql commands for keystone database reset

From commit b51d16f:
 * Make sure to apply the sysctl settings
 * Add a note about lost iptables rules after reboot
 * Define the my_ip setting for nova nodes
 * Use the controller IP addres to access horizon

Change-Id: I75669175a45049661fc36e4db528e71cd07c64e3

commit_message:
Fixes dict metadata query issue of HBase

Now HBase doesn't support query the metadata with the dictionary
type. For example, the metadata of Glance image always has the
metadata "properties" which is dictionary and has some attributes,
size, kernel id, etc. So this fix will enable the HBase driver of
CM to support query like "metadata.properties.tag=test".

Fixes bug 1206022

Change-Id: I7fa73cea94a948d47e27492dfb7e3a0e005ccb48

commit_message:
Enable debug logging on tempest

With tempest moving to testr (serially currently) the log level is no
longer defaulting to debug as it did with nose. To get the same level
of verbosity in the logging as when running with nose this commit
sets the debug flag on tempest.

Change-Id: I6acd57be0f8188d31825d88471ba9883ebb30519

Unless I'm mistaken, this could allow one thread to read while another thread is writing, which could cause problems.  Maybe that's accounted for in another way?

I've done something similar to this in the past, and that time I made it so a writer had to wait for any existing readers to complete before it could write, but once a writer was waiting no new readers could come in.  It worked well in a case where there was a lot of reading and only occasional writes.  Depending on the anticipated read/write balance you might need something different here. commit_message:
Add a Dynamic read-write lock

The patch adds a read-write lock whose name can be set dynamically when
calling the read / write method.

This patch is implemented as part of the blueprint
cache-backend-abstraction and will be used for synchronizing read /
write operations in a per-key basis.

Implements blueprint cache-backend-abstraction

Change-Id: I0820a98bec701f2b8ab9a707ecdf673a00af116f

Current master does now respect ratelimiting, since parsing of the
api-paste.ini was faulty. api-paste.ini limited user limiting by
setting a line as follows:
user:<user-id>:(GET, *, ".*", 4, minute) which was passed to the

limits = (POST, "*", .*, 10, MINUTE)

limits.<user-id2>:(GET, "*", .*, 2, minute)

commit_message:
Fix ratelimiting

Current master does now respect ratelimiting, since parsing of the
api-paste.ini was faulty. api-paste.ini limited user limiting by
setting a line as follows:
user:<user-id>:(GET, *, ".*", 4, minute) which was passed to the
Limiter as kwargs with "user" as a key. Thus multiple user limiting
was not possible as well as extracting the id of the user was bound
to fail, since we checked on the key with startswith("user:")

An example config in the api-paste.ini has to look as follows:
limits = (POST, "*", .*, 10, MINUTE)
limits.<user-id1>:(GET, "*", .*, 4, minute)
limits.<user-id2>:(GET, "*", .*, 2, minute)

Fixes bug: 1206976

Change-Id: I4adbe3dbe3a0bd607d6e675f230b0442b08ec791

commit_message:
test_glance.py: Stub out _get_member_model as well.

glanceclient's v2 client needs to also have its _get_member_model()
stubbed out as well, to avoid attempts to reach 'fake_host' during
client instantiation.

Update: Only stub when _get_member_model() when required.

Fixes: bug #1185178.

Cherry picked from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/30795

Change-Id: Ida47b3039c2539103fa3394d1443c896d7a81135

commit_message:
Add multiple storage backend support for IBM XIV

    * XIV Driver now works with the configuration object instead of FLAGS
    * XIV Driver now inherits San.SanDriver (Gain copy volume methods)

Change-Id: If9e8b80e47b9faa865df33b5f8db3eb32c2d0765
Fixes: bug #1179838

commit_message:
Initial input for HOT template guide and spec

This patch adds initial input for the HOT template guide and the HOT
specification.
Note that content so far is based on features implemented so far and
not forward-looking in any way. Whenever new features get implemented,
the guide and spec will be extended appropriately.

Contributes to blueprint hot-specification

Change-Id: I63d29ab0a1db6703b39f981161063d4fd9f97126

commit_message:
Don't raise ResourceFailure directly in Instance

It's meant to be a wrapper around other exceptions that's invoked by
top-level resource operations; don't use it as an all-purpose exception.

Change-Id: I295202bca603006a4d5f5d56110fc4298ddd9cec

commit_message:
Enable multi-cloud standalone mode

Adds a multi_cloud configuration parameter for auth_password that
tells a standalone Heat installation to look for its auth_url in
the request headers instead of the configuration file.  Also adds
an allowed_auth_uris configuration option to specify which
auth_urls are allowed as targets.

bp heat-multicloud

Change-Id: Ic0929586ac3b57c7f9f3335e0dbd5e14e6b56067

[{'created': '2013-08-12 05:09:59.000000000', 'message': "Kill ability to specify exchange in transport URL

My original thinking was that if you're using the exchange name to
separate two instances of the applications (so their queues don't
collide) then the exchange name is pretty key to transport
configuration. In fact, it's really a virtual host that you'd use for
this (at least in the case of rabbit and qpid).

Also, Nova's cells code has already moved ahead with the assumption that
the path specifies a virtual host, so it'd only make sense to deviate
from that if there was a really good reason to.

Change-Id: Ic8b5dc3538b6b17afec524047acc2efa76366377
"}]
commit_message:
Kill ability to specify exchange in transport URL

My original thinking was that if you're using the exchange name to
separate two instances of the applications (so their queues don't
collide) then the exchange name is pretty key to transport
configuration. In fact, it's really a virtual host that you'd use for
this (at least in the case of rabbit and qpid).

Also, Nova's cells code has already moved ahead with the assumption that
the path specifies a virtual host, so it'd only make sense to deviate
from that if there was a really good reason to.

Change-Id: Ic8b5dc3538b6b17afec524047acc2efa76366377

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-09 10:20:45.000000000', 'message': "Add thread-local store of request context

Oslo's logging code has some useful support for including bits of the request
context in log messages. While this isn't exclusively about the request context
in a dispatching RPC method, it seems useful for oslo.messaging to support the
concept for at least this use case simply by recording the context in a thread
local store before dispatching an endpoint method and immediately clearing it
when the method returns.

Note, we don't need to store weak refs in our store because we will clear the
reference in all cases rather than ever leaving a stale reference around in the
store.

Change-Id: I70ac06ed3a2a891a7a7b388b1823a0f3b08f2dd1
"}, {'created': '2013-08-09 10:21:32.000000000', 'message': "Add thread-local store of request context

Oslo's logging code has some useful support for including bits of the
request context in log messages. While this isn't exclusively about the
request context in a dispatching RPC method, it seems useful for
oslo.messaging to support the concept for at least this use case simply
by recording the context in a thread local store before dispatching an
endpoint method and immediately clearing it when the method returns.

Note, we don't need to store weak refs in our store because we will
clear the reference in all cases rather than ever leaving a stale
reference around in the store.

Change-Id: I70ac06ed3a2a891a7a7b388b1823a0f3b08f2dd1
"}]
commit_message:
Add thread-local store of request context

Oslo's logging code has some useful support for including bits of the
request context in log messages. While this isn't exclusively about the
request context in a dispatching RPC method, it seems useful for
oslo.messaging to support the concept for at least this use case simply
by recording the context in a thread local store before dispatching an
endpoint method and immediately clearing it when the method returns.

Note, we don't need to store weak refs in our store because we will
clear the reference in all cases rather than ever leaving a stale
reference around in the store.

Change-Id: I70ac06ed3a2a891a7a7b388b1823a0f3b08f2dd1

commit_message:
Add a context serialization hook

The client call() and cast() methods take a request context argument
which is expected to be a dictionary. The RPC endpoint methods on the
server are invoked with a dictionary context argument.

However, Nova passes a nova.context.RequestContext on the client side
and the oslo-incubator RPC code deserializes that as a amqp.RpcContext
which looks vaguely compatible with Nova's RequestContext.

Support the serialization and deserialization of RequestContext objects
with an additional (de)serialize_context() hook on our Serializer class.

Note: this is a backwards incompatible API change because Serializer
implementations which do not implement the new abstract methods would
no longer be possible to instantiate. Not a problem with this commit,
but shows the type of compat concerns we'll need to think about once the
API is locked down for good.

Change-Id: I20782bad77fa0b0e396d082df852ca355548f9b7

commit_message:
Resolved bug 746

Added verification that path param is starting with with '/'.
Resolved issue with incorrect code for '/' auto-stripping.

Param path should start with '/'. We could not have default
value for this param as '/' by few reasons:

   1)We could not declare default value for this param
     syntacticaly/semanticaly

   2)When user is working with services he should
     exactly know what he is doing. And making path
     parameter default value to '/'  going to hide some
     implementation details and also (what is very important)
     form incorrect impression about API behaviour.

Change-Id: I23aa0a0bb98211bc29c70cc0bf0cc26d924de1c2

commit_message:
Remove unused abstract class definitions

Fixes bug #1210281

Removed abstract classes definitions from DBTestBase and EventTestBase classes
in storage driver tests since they are not used.  Neither of these classes has
defined any abstract methods, so the abstract class definitions are unnecessary.

Also removed import statement for abstract base classes since there are now no
abstract class definitions.

Change-Id: I0b5b487631d780ba2ab087dce2ef340f126f8a69

Abandon this, please'}, {'account_id': 1313, 'date': '2013-03-30 18:08:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

from my point of view,it's a bug rather than a feature."}, {'account_id': 1313, 'date': '2013-03-30 20:08:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 5319, 'date': '2013-08-12 07:11:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Yaguang Tang: It seems what Jian Wen meant was that there is no network_api call for migrate_instance_start and migrate_instance_finish, so it's impossible to backport this bug.

Do you guys have any other work around that can be be implemented in the code? I need to do a hotfix on our Folsom version and releasing -> migrating > assign floating ip again wasn't an option for us. 

Is backporting the network_api.migrate_instance_start and finish calls from Grizzly do-able?"}, {'account_id': 1970, 'date': '2013-08-12 07:25:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sam, You are right. There are no such methods. And I didn't say that it was not a bug fix. It's a new feature as well as a bug fix. Generally, we can't backport a new feature to stable releases."}]

in multi_host mode.

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-07-11 13:53:44.000000000', 'message': 'Fix datetime precision issues in MySQL < 5.6

In MySQL versions prior to 5.6 DATETIME values are stored with seconds
precision, but datetime.datetime.utcnow() and timeutils.utcnow() return
datetime.datetime instances with microseconds precision. If such value
is stored and then retrieved from DB, the microseconds part will be lost.
This makes assertions comparing datetime values in tests fail.

This patch:
  - provides a test fixture that overrides timeutils.utcnow() so that
    it returns datetime instances with seconds precision
  - fixes a few tests that rely on microseconds precision of datetime
    values retrieved from DB

Blueprint: bp/db-api-tests-on-all-backends

Change-Id: I0da3b319b124b7fadbd3a721ae346b6f301ba7a2
'}, {'created': '2013-07-11 13:55:04.000000000', 'message': 'Fix datetime precision issues in MySQL < 5.6

In MySQL versions prior to 5.6 DATETIME values are stored with seconds
precision, but datetime.datetime.utcnow() and timeutils.utcnow() return
datetime.datetime instances with microseconds precision. If such value
is stored and then retrieved from DB, the microseconds part will be lost.
This makes assertions comparing datetime values in tests fail.

This patch:
  - provides a test fixture that overrides timeutils.utcnow() so that
    it returns datetime instances with seconds precision
  - fixes a few tests that rely on microseconds precision of datetime

commit_message:
Fix datetime precision issues in MySQL < 5.6

In MySQL versions prior to 5.6 DATETIME values are stored with seconds
precision, but datetime.datetime.utcnow() and timeutils.utcnow() return
datetime.datetime instances with microseconds precision. If such value
is stored and then retrieved from DB, the microseconds part will be lost.
This makes assertions comparing datetime values in tests fail.

Comparisons are the simplest case of test failures.  More interesting cases are
ones that make DB queries with DATETIME ranges or depend on the order of rows
sorted by DATETIME columns, etc.

As long as we can't have microseconds precision of stored DATETIME values in
production (for which MySQL < 5.6 is quite common), we'd better make the code
and tests not rely on microseconds precision in any way too.

This patch:
  - provides a test fixture that overrides timeutils.utcnow() so that
    it returns datetime instances with seconds precision
  - fixes a few tests that rely on microseconds precision of datetime
    values retrieved from DB

Blueprint: db-api-tests-on-all-backends

Change-Id: I0da3b319b124b7fadbd3a721ae346b6f301ba7a2

commit_message:
Use native methods for list manipulation

It's better to append a item to a list rather than creating a list instance
and extending it. Also the list class has its native method for extension.

Change-Id: If492c35822cd7d83b509692c2226612e565204d3

commit_message:
Port policy from oslo and refactor heat policy

This patch is to refactor Heat's usage to allow bringing the
policy code from oslo up to the current version to address
many fixed bugs which affect Heat.

    1. Refactor the heat wrapper policy.
    2. Add netaddr in requirement.txt.
    3. Add necessary unit test to cover the refactor part code.

Oslo commit: 3626b6db91ce1e897d1993fb4e13ac4237d04b7f
Fixes bug #1192551

Change-Id: Ia71d14b2cfde9110216ba38a515fee16d0f0c35e

commit_message:
Cleaned up an evil carryover from the past

It's inappropriate to use _ in the way that it was being used in this
function, especially in OpenStack where we do use gettext. Replace it
with the slightly more verbose but also slightly less broken 'stderr'.

Change-Id: I1b59dc4a787ca3a2e489e71135d90e97dbb1efaf

commit_message:
Stop copying stackrc out of clouds.

The static stackrc we embed in cloud images isn't suitable for using
from outside the cloud, instead we make one in the incubator which is.
We already did that for the under and overclouds, now do it for the
seed cloud too.

Fixes bug 1191650

Change-Id: Id5b6fa77191e5231df77192a900059069ebef6c6

commit_message:
Advise folk to sit in $TRIPLE_ROOT not incubator.

The incubator directory shouldn't be assumed to be the working
directory as our tools need to be installable.

Telling folk to cd to it makes it special and increases the chance of
accidentally making code assume it is the working directory.

Change-Id: Ib09407e1ce97fa5fd12d4b7387e57d04e9f002d3

commit_message:
Increase PXE deploy timeout.

Several users with slightly older hardware report the PXE deploy
process aborting deploys that were progressing fine. By increasing the
default PXE deploy timeout we should cater for this. A separate bug
has been filed in Nova/Ironic about the timeout being too simple.

Change-Id: I8ca0525ce57edb9256a35db54e955e1832279f64

commit_message:
Note that the included stackrc shouldn't be.

Cloud credentials are not machine specific, and global API state - so
by our principled separation of concerns they should be configured and
managed by API scripts rather than in-instance orchestation. Doing
that is a long term change, but documenting it can happen now.

Change-Id: I96c35cd26e2db10d12216b499ba72907366f5342

commit_message:
Increase PXE deploy timeout.

Several users with slightly older hardware report the PXE deploy
process aborting deploys that were progressing fine. By increasing the
default PXE deploy timeout we should cater for this. A separate bug
has been filed in Nova/Ironic about the timeout being too simple.

Change-Id: I9e340fc7f928b32b1146ce758cda7180888d6cc9

commit_message:
Ensure context type is handled when using to_dict

Handle the case where the context passed into def pack_context() is a
dictionary. If a dictionary is passed in, we don't need to call to_dict
before updating the msg.

fixes bug 1208971

Change-Id: I2ce0b28f97634e717868e0ee5525189338d4981c

commit_message:
Fix problem creating ResourceFailure

The ResourceFailure exception is being instantiated improperly in
a couple of places.  This changes fixes the problem and adds tests
to cover the problem cases.

Change-Id: I2662a3abde1fd00d275e2190401c20166256cae0
Closes-Bug: 1210681

I general I think this can be simplified using Joe's comment in patch set 2 about simply checking for code 409 and mapping that to request entity too large (unless Aaron knows of other cases where neutron would raise a 409 which aren't related to OverQuota)."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-08-08 18:18:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Eww, so I found there are 7 neutron exceptions which extend Conflict:

173: class AlreadyAttached(Conflict): 
179: class SubnetMismatchForPort(Conflict): 
200: class OverlappingAllocationPools(Conflict): 
218: class IpAddressGenerationFailure(Conflict): 
238: class OverQuota(Conflict): 
246: class InvalidQuotaValue(Conflict): 
251: class InvalidSharedSetting(Conflict): 

So translating 409 from neutron client to http request entity too large in nova is probably misleading, which I think is what Aaron was getting at.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-08-08 18:21:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Furthermore, python-neutronclient maps the neutron server exceptions to these:

    neutron_errors = {
        'NetworkNotFound': exceptions.NetworkNotFoundClient,
        'NetworkInUse': exceptions.NetworkInUseClient,
        'PortNotFound': exceptions.PortNotFoundClient,
        'RequestedStateInvalid': exceptions.StateInvalidClient,
        'PortInUse': exceptions.PortInUseClient,
        'AlreadyAttached': exceptions.AlreadyAttachedClient, }

So the only intersect between what neutron client maps and what neutron raises as a Conflict is AlreadyAttached.

It really seems like most of those neutron exceptions should be BadRequest or NotFound."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-08-08 20:00:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I'm working on a neutron patch to change SubnetMismatchForPort to a 400 code rather than 409.  I also opened neutron bug 1210274 for InvalidQuotaValue being a 409 when it should be a 400 or at least 403 to match it's own API docs."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-08-08 22:07:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Removing the unused AlreadyAttached conflict in neutron with this patch:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/40976/'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-08-08 22:53:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

wow this one went down the rabbit hole quickly'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-08-09 13:28:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Joe, sadly that seems to be the case with most of the patches I've seen that try to solve problems like this. I think the biggest problem is the lack of parity in neutron exceptions from the client so nova has a hard time figuring out what's what and mapping them correctly. As pointed out, I've got 3 patches out to neutron to cleanup exceptions (either change from 409 or remove unused exceptions which were a 409). At the end of the day, however, I think the answer is going to be we need to get an OverQuotaNeutronClientException into the neutron client so we can catch that directly in nova and map to a 413 or whatever we use for over-quota exceptions in nova."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-08-09 17:13:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Matt, there is a blueprint in oslo to have unified client exceptions, now I really see the value of it.

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo/+spec/common-client-library'}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2013-08-09 17:27:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(10:21:44 AM) arosen: mlavalle: mriedem I think if we catch a 409 here: 
(10:21:48 AM) arosen: https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/network/security_group/neutron_driver.py#L59
(10:21:48 AM) arosen: https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/network/security_group/neutron_driver.py#L197
(10:21:48 AM) arosen: and raise nova.exception.SecurityGroupLimitExceeded() we should be okay. 
(10:22:30 AM) arosen: Neutron will return 409 if you try to create a security gr'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-08-09 17:53:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Here is the IRC conversation between myself and Aaron about how we think this is best attacked:

http://paste.openstack.org/show/43725/'}, {'account_id': 4694, 'date': '2013-08-10 17:10:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

arosen, mriedem. Thanks for the help. I got the message and I will work on catching the 409 in  https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/network/security_group/neutron_driver.py#L59 and https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/network/security_group/neutron_driver.py#L197 and raise nova.exception.SecurityGroupLimitExceeded()'}, {'account_id': 4694, 'date': '2013-08-12 02:15:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

arosen, mriedem: I am abandoning this patchset. Per our conversation in Gerrit, this patchset is now replaced by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/41329/'}, {'account_id': 4694, 'date': '2013-08-12 02:16:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Abandoned

[{'created': '2013-07-29 01:48:29.000000000', 'message': 'Handle NeutronClientException when quota exceeded

When networking is provided by Neutron and a security group or a security group
rule quota is exceeded, we get a NeutronClientException with status_code 409
and message "NeutronClientException: Quota exceeded for resources"

and translate it correctly to HTTPRequestEntityTooLarge

patch

commit_message:
Handle NeutronClientException when quota exceeded

When networking is provided by Neutron and a security group or a security group
rules quota is exceeded, we get a NeutronClientException with status_code 409
and message "NeutronClientException: Quota exceeded for resources"

This patch modifies function translate_exceptions() to capture this exception
and translate it correctly to HTTPRequestEntityTooLarge

test_neutron_security_groups is also updated to provide a unit test for this
patch

Fixes: bug #1209446

Change-Id: I4c087684ef77988e5f463d7f2f50fc2a04f37db0

commit_message:
Security Guide: Markup of links

The guide does not use markup of links at all, I've started adding
markup to the first chapters. I've also did some minor cleanups I
noticed.

Patch set 2:
Diane, thanks for the review, I've followed all your suggestions.

Patch set 3:
I've fixed the name of the OpenStack Compute Adminstration Guide
everywhere in my patch set.

Patch set 4:
Fix whitespace

Patch set 5:
Fix remaining chapters

Change-Id: I3c11aab2bafadd7f2ee3742fbfcaa7f937102d0d

commit_message:
Add option to run testr serially

This commit adds a new serial option to testr_command.py that when
set will run testr serially instead of running testr with the
'--parallel' flag.

Change-Id: Id49b105dc921e9acdef1a94d933719ad3a772c81

commit_message:
Add note why E712 is ignored

According to the commit message in
560e5cd84ef2c1a6427c78d35eedc66445e1f77f we ignore E712 because '
With this change we ignore E712 since it is normal to use
"column == True" in sqlalchemy.'

Add note in tox.ini explaining this.

Change-Id: I393e13b1430aae46f958311875678bd99e17b13c

'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-08-02 18:17:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

erm, the `page` and `per_page` ones have basically remained in the doc as not much more than notes, afaik (they've never been implemented, and we do support pagination via implementation-defined `next` and `previous` links on collections, where we don't have to define how the query parameters are implemented). i'd propose removing `page` and `per_page` entirely, and documenting the rest a bit more formally as actual markdown lists (rather than using a hack that gerrit can't render properly), e.g.:

  Query parameters:

  - `type={service_type}` (optional): filter the collection by service type"}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2013-08-05 22:14:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Work In Progress

[{'created': '2013-08-01 22:44:27.000000000', 'message': "Format query_string sections

When the markdown doc is rendered to HTML, the sections that
list the query string options are all on one line so are hard
to interpret. Turns out you can inject a line break by ending
the line with a couple of spaces, according to some docs[0].
Looks bad in the review tool, but it's a lot easier to read
when rendered.

[0] http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/syntax

Change-Id: If1701e0b8c022bf63bafce179da0d1f8fade3239

commit_message:
pagination is not supported

The Keystone server doesn't support pagination, so the Identity
API spec shouldn't mention it.

Change-Id: If1701e0b8c022bf63bafce179da0d1f8fade3239

[{'created': '2013-08-09 18:33:17.000000000', 'message': 'Define a Schema format for properties

Define a Schema class for properties and their constraints that is easily
serialisable to a JSON schema format that matches the proposed Parameter
input syntax for HOT. Since resource properties have not been exposed to
the user before, this format will make the most sense to a user in the long
term.

A future patch will switch the Property validation code over to using
Schema objects instead of the dictionary-based schemata currently in use.

blueprint resource-properties-schema

Change-Id: I79fa5927bdffeaf103a1c2ba58b709b4ba72b551
'}]
commit_message:
Define a Schema format for properties

Define a Schema class for properties and their constraints that is easily
serialisable to a JSON schema format that matches the proposed Parameter
input syntax for HOT. Since resource properties have not been exposed to
the user before, this format will make the most sense to a user in the long
term.

A future patch will switch the Property validation code over to using
Schema objects instead of the dictionary-based schemata currently in use.

blueprint resource-properties-schema

Change-Id: I79fa5927bdffeaf103a1c2ba58b709b4ba72b551

commit_message:
Handle disk constraint failures during live migration

Reports from Nova-Compute are reported back as RemoteError
due to the RPC calls. Treat any RPC RemoteError as an
invalid host and continue scheduling.

Fixes LP Bug #1199885

Change-Id: Icec87910b039afc538d503542b786e50987d6b0e

commit_message:
Update requirements in integration test

So that we don't test combinations of things that we won't see in the
gate, run the same requirements sync job that devstack does.

Change-Id: I0ee375b4e41aa214acf4cd3bfeb1b3a8ccb08dff

commit_message:
Deprecate conductor's compute_reboot() interface

We no longer need to run reboot() actions through conductor to avoid
the instance action database hit that compute_api.stop() would
entail. This deprecates that interface and makes the manager use
the compute_api method directly.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I86c70fb33b023d55d88a64de1fa6c39c10fd7b01

commit_message:
Deprecate conductor's compute_stop() interface

We no longer need to run stop() actions through conductor to avoid
the instance action database hit that compute_api.stop() would
entail. This deprecates that interface and makes the manager use
the compute_api method directly.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I11ab8fadb3e417b5256504699603e8111ed69f7f

commit_message:
Make compute_api use InstanceAction object

This makes the compute_api instance action code use objects instead
of direct-to-database calls. This should open the door for deprecating
some conductor proxies for compute_api that help compute manager
avoid the database hit required for the instance action to complete.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: If622d8079ca2897b0d5094e9341e29cde7c1ff59

commit_message:
Add basic InstanceAction object

This adds a basic InstanceAction object with the ability to provide
the functionality needed to satisfy compute_api's use of actions.
The ability to finish an action by uuid in a sort of out-of-body
way (as it is done now) is provided, as well as an instance method
for a (hopefully) future scenario where actions are started, carried,
and finished when appropriate.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I094645b065575bbbce35ed18bf6901cbbf4e383d

commit_message:
Add delete() operation to InstanceInfoCache

This adds the trivial delete() operation to InstanceInfoCache
and makes the _local_delete() path in compute_api use it.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: Iac4c36c1158ca98f3a2ab011f151ccd2a9ebeac0

commit_message:
Make compute_api use Instance.destroy()

This makes the places in compute_api that call db.instance_destroy()
use the object.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I6cb0704e8c5420c2aaa4392bbf20c48941e2e044

subject: Add Instance.destroy()

commit_message:
Add Instance.destroy()

This adds destroy support to Instance.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I5622bd98c9fb6d880b3e5ebfbc60f8c4f190c8e5

commit_message:
Make compute_api use Instance.create()

This makes compute_api use Instance.create() instead of the
db.instance_create() API.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I2ca1232fd9e12ca2fb57cd2acaa27ebd8aaa6dbe

[{'created': '2013-08-10 18:26:41.000000000', 'message': "Add H233 to ignores in tox.ini

The auto-pull of updated libs added to devstack
will result in the python 3.3 print checks being
added which we're not ready for.

Temporarily add this to our tox.ini ignore list
until we have a chance to go through and fix all fo these

commit_message:
Add H233 to ignores in tox.ini

The auto-pull of updated libs added to devstack
will result in the python 3.3 print checks being
added which we're not ready for.

Temporarily add this to our tox.ini ignore list
until we have a chance to go through and fix these.

Change-Id: Ie6e0e28433e9b1240b94ed4a323a97a85e475a17

commit_message:
add option for adding a suffix to output files

When we run update.py automatically in the devstack gate, we
have the issue that we are programatically changing files which
are actually git versioned. This makes lots of people sad pandas.

As this is all being done automatically we could actually update
the files with a suffix, then have devstack use that instead.
This will make developers happy, as they won't have to keep
resetting their devstack trees if they do development straight in
them.

Change-Id: I3d264f15ab7123f258f198b375b9667895c4104c

else gave a negative vote on the same patchset.

Allow using a pypi mirror to install via pip.

Using a custom pypi mirror can be very convenient, making image builds
substantially faster - because we create multiple virtual
environments we benefit more than single-virtualenv users would.

commit_message:
Fix H501, String formatting should not use locals()

This is the last warning remaining from Hacking 0.6,
so allow Hacking 0.6 to be used as well by updating
the test-requirements constraint.

Change-Id: Iedb5873003dc5762afe37d52dfe4ec26d346edf1

commit_message:
Test cases for Roles V3 Actions

This submission adds 'test_roles.py' test script with test cases
so as to verify the functionality of all 'role' actions available
in V3 keystone api. And also with required support functions in
identity_client.py of both JSON/XML interfaces

Change-Id: I79f0a68ab62e7d86b5789e5e6f938621b35cf70b
Implements: blueprint keystone-v3-roles-test

commit_message:
Support heat in standalone mode.

The following localrc will launch only heat in standalone mode
and allow it to provision within the openstack specified by
the configured keystone endpoint:
HEAT_STANDALONE=True
ENABLED_SERVICES=rabbit,mysql,heat,h-api,h-api-cfn,h-api-cw,h-eng
KEYSTONE_SERVICE_HOST=...
KEYSTONE_AUTH_HOST=...

Change-Id: I0d8a541fc9d592577423b074c789829f8b8d6702

This commit removes the posargs from the coverage job's testr line
which will not work with the coverage periodic jenkins. It also adds
posargs to the 'all' job which will enable running a single test using
tox.

Change-Id: I650531377be7f58d18f79addefc32e62a4c268ea
"}]
commit_message:
Fix posargs usage for tox jobs

This commit removes the posargs from the coverage job's testr line
which will not work with the coverage periodic jenkins. It also adds
posargs to the 'all' job which will enable running a single test using
tox.

Change-Id: I650531377be7f58d18f79addefc32e62a4c268ea

Correct Ops Guide PDF link to avoid 404!

As noted in the bug report, the 'get the PDF' link was broken.

This patch changes the guide to point to the trunk links.

Change-Id: I74cfd864b51058bcee5a4a002a4d1c3aab85b656

Reimplements abandoned patch
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/22415

Implements a new configuration parameter to choose the
auth strategy for ssh enabled tests:
- password base (current implementation)
- public key based (new default)
Modifies compute test base class to create a server
resources with keypair pubkey is enabled.
Enables run_ssh flag in tempest.conf.sample.
Updates relevant tests to use the create_server
wrapper method in BaseComputeTest.

Implements: blueprint ssh-auth-strategy

Skips instance name check until bug #1207308 is fixed

Change-Id: I2015b7163063aa4ca7cc786b36d3939170fa7022
'}]
commit_message:
Support for ssh auth to VMs via public key

Reimplements abandoned patch
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/22415

Implements a new configuration parameter to choose the
auth strategy for ssh enabled tests:
- password base (current implementation)
- public key based (new default)
Modifies compute test base class to create a server
resources with keypair pubkey is enabled.
Enables run_ssh flag in tempest.conf.sample.
Updates relevant tests to use the create_server
wrapper method in BaseComputeTest.

Implements: blueprint ssh-auth-strategy

Skips instance name check until bug #1207308 is fixed

Change-Id: I2015b7163063aa4ca7cc786b36d3939170fa7022

commit_message:
keystoneclient get users by id when id is not uuid

This removes the uuid requirement in utils.py/find_resource. When
ldap is in use, and we do not control the id field, it cannot be
forced to search for a uuid.

Change-Id: I3d1afa9e56b95ce2c016c05c5f3fc90f7fad325e
Fixes: bug #1204214

'}, {'created': '2013-07-16 09:23:55.000000000', 'message': "Create snaphot command implemented with taskflow.

Implement create_snaphot command using new version of taskflow:

1. Flow is described as a sequence of actions.
   User-defined actions are called 'tasks'.
2. Each action can be executed or reverted.
3. Flow reverts all executed actions when some task fails.
4. _cerate_snapshot method was splitted on tasks. Tasks that can be common
   for different commands was moved to common_tasks.py.
5. Flow catches and saves an exception, then reverts tasks and throws it again.

ToDo:
1. Implement locks for used resources.
2. Run flow in the separate thread, that'll allow to stop and resume it.

New taskflow patch is here https://review.openstack.org/#/c/36472/

Change-Id: I012c34453d12af1aba6a34ae71b3ee86620b4041

commit_message:
Create snaphot command implemented with taskflow.

Implement create_snaphot command using new version of taskflow:

1. Flow is described as a sequence of actions.
   User-defined actions are called 'tasks'.
2. Each action can be executed or reverted.
3. Flow reverts all executed actions when some task fails.
4. _create_snapshot method was splitted on tasks. Tasks that can be common
   for different commands was moved to common_tasks.py.
5. Flow catches and saves an exception, then reverts tasks and throws it again.

New taskflow patch is I8d9fae1235756b2a8398d7c80454dcb1bcb4a78c.

Change-Id: I012c34453d12af1aba6a34ae71b3ee86620b4041

[{'created': '2013-08-01 22:19:54.000000000', 'message': 'Enforce unique tunnel IDs for endpoints

Tunnel endpoints can never overlap.  There is the possibility
of a race condition during the tunnel id generation (we have
seen this in production with large numbers of nodes) with the
way the unique tunnel id is generated (max of last known id).

This database constraint ensures we will never allow bad data
into the database in the first place since we would rather have
network creation fail when a race condition occurs then database
persisted misconfigured tunnels to debug.

Change-Id: I90c095543852895a1930d11ba1fdf4d06f8faef7
'}]
commit_message:
Enforce unique tunnel IDs for endpoints

Tunnel endpoints can never overlap.  There is the possibility
of a race condition during the tunnel id generation (we have
seen this in production with large numbers of nodes) with the
way the unique tunnel id is generated (max of last known id).

This database constraint ensures we will never allow bad data
into the database in the first place since we would rather have
network creation fail when a race condition occurs then database
persisted misconfigured tunnels to debug.

Change-Id: I90c095543852895a1930d11ba1fdf4d06f8faef7

commit_message:
fix gettext calls to work on uninterpolated strings

gettext needs to run before the interpolation
for the lookup to work

Fixes bug: 1210337

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-07-12 08:59:52.000000000', 'message': 'Fix the multi-backend storge issue for ZMQ.

This issue is not caused by the naming convention as described in Bug 1166899,
but due to the incorrect node_topic registration in ZMQ.

What have been done in this patch:
*Import the latest impl_zmq.py from oslo.
*Remove self.manager.init_host(). This line will cause error, if ZMQ is chosen
as the MQ.
*Change the delimiter from "." to ":" between topic and host. "." will make
node_topic an invalid key for the registration in ZMQ.
*The node_topic should be registered correctly via
topic = '.'.join((topic, CONF.rpc_zmq_host)) in impl_zmq.py.

Fixed Bug 1166899.

Change-Id: Id982ab9482f08d69bdc68d389fb41a7752efa168

commit_message:
Fix the multi-backend storge issue for ZMQ.

This issue is not caused by the naming convention as described in Bug 1166899,
but due to the incorrect node_topic registration in ZMQ.

What have been done in this patch:
*Import the latest impl_zmq.py from oslo.
*Change the delimiter from "." to ":" between topic and host. "." will make
node_topic an invalid key for the registration in ZMQ.
*The node_topic should be registered correctly via
topic = '.'.join((topic, CONF.rpc_zmq_host)) in impl_zmq.py.
*Move init_host() in services.py downstairs to make sure the c-vol can be
launched successfully for ZMQ.

Fixed Bug 1166899.

Change-Id: Id982ab9482f08d69bdc68d389fb41a7752efa168

This allows for tabs to be disabled in Horizon via a config setting
in settings.HORIZON_CONFIG['disabled_tabs']

Example:

HORIZON_CONFIG = {

}

Fixes Bug: 1210419

commit_message:
Customization: Add an explicit example of disabling Floating IPs

The current documentation on customizing focuses on
registering/unregistering components.  While this is simple and
effective at a high-level, fine-grained customizations like overriding
individual allowed() methods uses a different approach.

This confuses n00bcakes like myself, so add an explicit example of
dropping Floating IPs support to spell it out.

Fixes Bug: 1210419

Change-Id: Ib9b1579b33d48c7b2bd9bf3ad96cd303210a4420

commit_message:
Refactoring of user assignment workflow.

The javascript code and template for project membership has been
renamed to horizon.membership.js. It has been modified to take
step_slug as an argument, this is used as the identifier for the
membership step variables - for supporting multiple membership step
in a single workflow.

Also, removed unused template, tables and views.

Change-Id: I8685a307006cabc7005def160875c844e24c60ef
Fixes bug 1208558

commit_message:
Added basic helper for map-reduce actions

* Added mapreduce action
* It doesn't include streaming and pipes actions
* Refactored base_workflow creator to hide common methods
* Unit-test added

Implements blueprint edp-oozie-workflow-creator

Change-Id: Iabb03f93ff0eacd875b471646afdc0f65aebc416

commit_message:
Add Autogenerate-config-doc code to tools

This patch brings the auto-generate-config doc tool into
the openstack-manuals repo, where it can be used to update
the configuration option tables.

patchset2 fixes obvious things noted by reviewers, likely

commit_message:
Add Replication Network feature documentation

Replication network support was added to 1.9.0 release of
Swift. This update includes instructions how to configure
this feature and description of how it generally works.
More specific information on the replication network was
added to Swift Developer documentation.

bug #1123067

Change-Id: I1cebec7c105690e9be72f314fc3aaecdfaf2e3f9

[{'created': '2013-08-09 17:45:58.000000000', 'message': "cleanup potentially installed older oslo.config

If the user had oslo.config installed prior to us setting up the
oslo.config out of git they can get themselves into this very funny
situation where pip doesn't see oslo.config 1.1.x, however some
packages might. This manifests itself as a user error trying to
start nova-api which uses DeprecatedOption, not in oslo.config 1.1.x

Because of the funny state pip is in, you can't uninstall oslo.config.

So in these situations, if we see old oslo.config in the filesystem,
pip install / uninstall it to ensure that everyone ends up using the
git version instead.

To reduce the amount of user confusion, do this on every
install_oslo for a while, which we can purge after Havana ships.

Change-Id: If92073be5a431840701c952a194e63a7c452c9ca

commit_message:
cleanup potentially installed older oslo.config

If the user had oslo.config installed prior to us setting up the
oslo.config out of git they can get themselves into this very funny
situation where pip doesn't see oslo.config 1.1.x, however some
packages might. This manifests itself as a user error trying to
start nova-api which uses DeprecatedOption, not in oslo.config 1.1.x

Because of the funny state pip is in, you can't uninstall oslo.config.

So in these situations, if we see old oslo.config in the filesystem,
pip install / uninstall it to ensure that everyone ends up using the
git version instead.

To reduce the amount of user confusion, do this on every
install_oslo for a while, which we can purge after Havana ships.

Change-Id: If92073be5a431840701c952a194e63a7c452c9ca

commit_message:
Abstract out attribute_ignore assigning in LDAP driver

This is used to avoid code duplication in keystone/identity/
backends/ldap.py. All changes are fully covered by test_*option_
name*_attribute_ignore() in test_backend_ldap.py.

bp refactor-ldap-driver

Change-Id: Ia0fc0b3d4a92416dcd65ddb49b3b0bf9a0777363

Create default role on demand

When adding a user to a project, if the default role is missing, create it.

Bug 1176270

Change-Id: Id972ccf9c132c362a0b85049d248530dc2d56d54

commit_message:
Remove OpenStack Reactions from Planet

Based on mailing list discussion at
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/community/2013-August/000431.html

it seems that OpenStack Reactions is not meeting the criteria of what
people expect to be on the planet.openstack.org blog aggregator.

This patch removes it from the feed.

Change-Id: Ibaf480cc069621ecd050b1d7e9501511596f77a2

commit_message:
Fix simultaneous timeout with smart iptables usage

Simultaneous boots were getting timeouts in allocate_for_network.
This was due to our inefficient use of iptables where we attempt
to recreate the same rules over and over using initialize_gateway,
plug, and restart_dhcp.

This patch makes the iptables code a little bit smarter by only
shelling out if the rule list has changed. Note that there is
a small difference in the interpretation of duplicate rules.
Previously, the last copy of the rule would win whereas now
the first copy of the rule will win. Multiple copies of the same
rule were never supported. This means the only thing that one
needs to remember is it is necessary to remove a rule and re-add
it if you want to move it later in the list.

Fixes bug 1199433

Change-Id: I9920f8d6aa269d9b3bfd88a8dbbb00f859deb158

commit_message:
Address config incompatibility introduced with oslo.config >= 1.2.0

This patch changes how nvp cluster specific configuration is retrieved
from nvp.ini so that it no longer relies on _cparser, which has been
removed in newer versions of oslo.config.

Fixes bug #1200609

Change-Id: I631c6584ca6b45d0f716533bd1d711d049c6f157

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-07-01 22:18:32.000000000', 'message': 'Support setting block size for block devives

cinder now support backend with different block sizes. Sometimes
we need to set a specific block size or operations against the
backend will result in I/O errors. Additionally its a good idea
to tune the block sizes to the correct size as it can improve I/O
performance.

The basic disk configuration for libvrit now supports setting the
logical and physical block size of devices. It relys on the cinder
volume service to return the appopriate block sizes for a given
volume (if supported).

By default it does not set the block sizes which defaults to
512 bytes.

Change-Id: I77adc96b340680218f82bbef8f9ec14711d26a7f
Fixes: #1195913
'}, {'created': '2013-07-02 04:08:15.000000000', 'message': 'Support setting block size for block devives

cinder now support backend with different block sizes. Sometimes
we need to set a specific block size or operations against the
backend will result in I/O errors. Additionally its a good idea
to tune the block sizes to the correct size as it can improve I/O
performance.

The basic disk configuration for libvrit now supports setting the
logical and physical block size of devices. We pull the block size
from the volume metadata and store it in the connection_info of
the block_device_mapping table for use later.

By default it does not set the block sizes which defaults to
512 bytes.

Change-Id: I77adc96b340680218f82bbef8f9ec14711d26a7f
Fixes: #1195913

cinder now supports backend with different block sizes. Sometimes
we need to set a specific block size or operations against the
backend will result in I/O errors. Additionally its a good idea

The basic disk configuration for libvrit now supports setting the
logical and physical block size of devices. We pull the block size
from the volume metadata and store it in the connection_info of

By default it does not set the block sizes which defaults to

DocImpact:
This feature requires libvirt 0.10.2+ and the QEMU or KVM
hpypervisor. If a volume has a custom block size, the hypervisor
and libvirt version are checked during the attach_volume call. If
the hypervisor is not supported or the libvirt version is too old
the attach is aborted and an exception is raised.

Change-Id: I77adc96b340680218f82bbef8f9ec14711d26a7f
Fixes Bug #1195913
