commit_message:
Support setting block size for block devices

cinder now supports backend with different block sizes. Sometimes
we need to set a specific block size or operations against the
backend will result in I/O errors. Additionally its a good idea
to tune the block sizes to the correct size as it can improve I/O
performance.

The basic disk configuration for libvrit now supports setting the
logical and physical block size of devices.  The block size info
is stored in connection_info of the block_device_mapping table
for later use.

By default it does not set the block sizes which defaults to
512 bytes.

DocImpact:
This feature requires libvirt 0.10.2+ and the QEMU or KVM
hypervisor. If a volume has a custom block size, cinder considers
it required. As such the hypervisor and libvirt version are
checked during the attach_volume call. If the hypervisor is not
supported or the libvirt version is too old the attach is
aborted and an exception is raised.

Change-Id: I77adc96b340680218f82bbef8f9ec14711d26a7f
Fixes Bug #1195913

commit_message:
Fix broken database migration for Cisco plugin

Remove migration for a table that was never used.
Correct table drop order due to foreignkey dependency.

Closes bug: #1210219

Change-Id: I38bcedf7a84967bea2c1679a6a6ab51a9451b33a

commit_message:
Port server_usage API to v3 part 1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. The copy as-is will not be loaded by either
the v2 or v3 extension loaders. The second changeset will then
make the changes required for it to work as a v3 extension.

This is being done in order to make reviewing of extension
porting easier as gerrit will display only what is actually
changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Ie5cbde7d9a0d77e78c9f9cc577d8cbd36fb74188

commit_message:
Get hypervisor type from libvirt type

When we use "nova hypervisor-show <id>", we need to show
the correct hypervisor_type, so we get hypervisor type from
libvirt type in nova.conf.

Fixes bug #1195361

Change-Id: I945a30747e945ea420fe1ca32daa92f04db13a13

commit_message:
Sync unified logging solution from Oslo

This commit introduces a unified logging strategy from oslo-incubator in
an attempt to standardize logging in Keystone similar to other OpenStack
projects (Nova, Quantum, etc.). This commit only introduces
oslo-incubator/openstack/common/log.py and it's dependencies.
Implementation of this logging solution will be purposed later.

blueprint unified-logging-in-keystone

Change-Id: I860c0f0e935fcd7b4c4886ffd54bf22f2cf4cbb3

commit_message:
Use OS_CONFIG_FILES to populate metadata tree

Building on the lower level interface, now we can start operating in
a way that will work smoothly with os-collect-config.

This makes apply_config.read_config redundant, so it is removed.

We now parse the environment variable OS_CONFIG_FILES, as defined by
os-collect-config's documentation. The colon separated list is used
to determine the json config files to parse and merge.

Change-Id: I2a2eb7c4d2a3d06a73258cadcae4e7fe4bbb0096

commit_message:
Reverse order of fallback/new config file handling

We must read the "fallback" files first, otherwise the old values will
override the new values that os-collect-config has picked up from its
sources.

Change-Id: I6ec7958adc9690b68614c4ff48a18607e07746ea

commit_message:
Buffer message documents when enqueuing them, in lieu of streaming

This patch modifies the pipeline for the message post operation
to use list comprehensions in place of generators. This simplifies
some existing logic (e.g., retry handling) and sets us up nicely
for input validation. It should also be a little bit faster than
the previous approach, at the expense of increased memory usage.

Note that the SQLite driver was not modified (YAGNI).

Change-Id: Iae5f7ceaf09f775afc4a4944e0c626d2f40a6554
Implements: blueprint buffer-messages

This is a simple patch that renames two "helpers" modules
to make them consistent with the storage driver naming scheme.

Not sure where to put this, but I'll toss it in here for now; there were some mentions of Token Revocation and Token Chaining. 

Token Revocation - The consumer uses Access Tokens to request valid Keystone Tokens. There is an API that the authorizing user can call to delete the consumer's Access Token. Thereby removing the consumers ability to request *new* valid Keystone Tokens. In the same delete call, the backend will also delete any Keystone Tokens associated with the authorizing User. So in case the consumer had any Keystone Tokens, they would now be invalid. 

One thing I am unsure of is: Say the authorizing User has a role revoked; the Access Token will not be updated. The consumer can try to request a new Keystone Token with the same old user_id, project_id and (what was authorized) roles. Would the Keystone Token backend would prevent this from completing? Since the User no longer has the Role.

Token Chaining - Using a Keystone Token to retrieve another Keystone Token. I'm of the opinion that this is a non-issue, sine the Consumer can use the Access Token to request Keystone Tokens anyway. As mentioned above, if a Consumer's Access Token is deleted, then its Keystone Tokens are now invalid. Maybe I am missing something?"}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-07-17 16:06:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Add delegated auth via oauth to keystone

Provide the ability for identity users to delegate roles to third party
consumers via the OAuth 1.0a specification. This functionality is being
provided as an extension.

blueprint: delegated-auth-via-oauth

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: Ic9b6c6f0643e4b83795b2d0426e3570cd83b55c4

commit_message:
Adding interface for os-collect-config

When run (indirectly via os-refresh-config) under os-collect-config, we
expect to receive a list of json files in the environment variable
OS_CONFIG_FILES. Os-collect-config does not define the intended behavior
of consumers of these files, but does suggest that the order is
preserved if the os-collect-config user changes it.

With the order, we adopt a deep merge strategy where later config files
override earlier ones when there is a direct conflict. The end result is
the ability to pull data from many more sources into os-apply-config
templates.

We only provide an implementation and tests in this commit. A later
commit will integrate it into the program and remove the old code.

Change-Id: Id6794a1df1b0cbdfe11f2cf1c2980ab84388b6b8

commit_message:
Tolerance for modified ceilometer alarm notification

Changes to the ceilometer alarm notification payload are
proposed here:

  https://review.openstack.org/40955
  https://review.openstack.org/41056

i.e. field names in the JSON payload are changed with:

  s/state/current/
  s/alarm/alarm_id/

Tolerance is added to the autoscaling logic for the new
field names.

Change-Id: I19f36d9331b6f28a3195fb5012ea0b9ee274ade3

commit_message:
Enable flag to update requirements on run

In order to serve the needs not only of the gate, but also of users
using devstack for development, we want to put the updating logic behind
a variable. Set that variable to true, so that the gate always runs the
update.

Change-Id: Id8c06070229f4da430163b99f242aa2c3fa8d90c

[{'created': '2013-07-30 01:16:35.000000000', 'message': 'Adds factory methods to load Hyper-V utils classes

Blueprint: hyper-v-wmi-v2

This patchset provides further decoupling between the ops modules
(e.g. vmops, volumeops) and the utils modules which handle the
interaction with the underlying OS.

The main reason for this refactoring is the need to provide an
implementation of the Hyper-V WMI V2 API (root\virtualization\v2)
that replace the initial version introduced with Hyper-V Server
2008.

Change-Id: I8a2dd8f7dea2e4044525866a0ab26211eb17bf99
'}]
commit_message:
Adds factory methods to load Hyper-V utils classes

Blueprint: hyper-v-wmi-v2

This patchset provides further decoupling between the ops modules
(e.g. vmops, volumeops) and the utils modules which handle the
interaction with the underlying OS.

The main reason for this refactoring is the need to provide an
implementation of the Hyper-V WMI V2 API (root\virtualization\v2)
that replace the initial version introduced with Hyper-V Server
2008.

Change-Id: I8a2dd8f7dea2e4044525866a0ab26211eb17bf99

commit_message:
Added Memory Persistence API and Generic Datatypes

Added a generic persistence API for JobBoards,
Jobs, LogBooks, Workflows, FlowDetails, Tasks,
and TaskDetails. The currently implemented
backends are in-memory. Also implemented generic
return types (listed above) for the generic API.

Change-Id: I6d09860ee08a900faf2c213a230429bf9e0dec01

'}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2013-08-01 07:45:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

A couple of questions:

1) What would be the case for other plugins to redefine default status?
2) Which plugins will use this?
3) Network status is not allowed to be specified on network creation and can't be updated (see neutron.api.v2.attributes). So if some plugin uses this ability to set network status other than default, how will it be changed?
4) Could you please add simple unit test for the change?"}, {'account_id': 1894, 'date': '2013-08-01 08:35:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

1) What would be the case for other plugins to redefine default status?

Mostly the same as ports.

Case1: Plugin is not sure that network build successfully when adding entry to DB. So it set status 'BUILD'.
Case2: Plugin create network on its backend then create DB entry including status on the backend (maybe 'ERROR'). In this case we can reduce DB commits.


2) Which plugins will use this?

NEC Plugin at least.


3) Network status is not allowed to be specified on network creation and can't be updated (see neutron.api.v2.attributes). So if some plugin uses this ability to set network status other than default, how will it be changed?

No, Neutron user cannot post/put status. These request will refuse in API layer.

Some plugins inherit NeutronDbPluginV2 and wrap create_network() to do some jobs to their backend around NeutronDbPluginV2.create_network(). They call NeutronDbPluginV2.create_network() with passing the same inputs as they had for now. So plugins can change input of NeutronDbPluginV2.create_network().


4) Could you please add simple unit test for the change?

Sure."}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2013-08-01 08:59:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: No score

Thanks for replies.

I'm not quite get #3. In which case do you plan to change network status from WHATEVER to ACTIVE?"}, {'account_id': 1894, 'date': '2013-08-01 13:27:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sorry, I think I'm missing your point...


AIUI, 'status' is set by plugin to expose resource status. So it does not have to be 'ACTIVE' in the end of creation.

I am planning to use this ability in two cases at NEC Plugin.

* In Case2 (explained previous comment): When Neutron user requests a new network, the plugin first create network on its backend and get status of the resource made on the backend. That status could be 'ACTIVE' or 'ERROR'. Then create DB entry with that status by adding {'status': XXX} to the network dictionary.

* In the case mentioned in commit message: When Neutron user requests a new network with admin_state_up=False, then plugin create DB entry with status='DOWN'. (In NEC Plugin, network.status='DOWN' means no packets are transported.)"}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2013-08-01 20:15:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

This commit makes NeutronDbPluginV2 get network status from input at
create_network() to allow other plugins to set network status while
creating DB entry.

Now plugins can create network with any status in a single DB commit.
(e.g. Set network status to 'DOWN' when admin_state_up is False.)

commit_message:
Make DbPlugin accept status in create_network().

This commit makes NeutronDbPluginV2 get network status from input at
create_network() to allow other plugins to set network status while
creating DB entry.

Now plugins can create network with any status in a single DB commit.
(e.g. Set network status to 'DOWN' when admin_state_up is False.)

This commit also changes NeutronDbPluginV2TestCase() to make default
network status configurable in each plugin test case.

Fixes: bug #1207167
Change-Id: Id3ad26719036c631e4b268150407a2c69919203f

commit_message:
xenapi: send identity headers from glance plugin

Send identity headers while uploading/downloading images from glance. Related
to:

1) Add identity headers while calling glanceclient from nova
Ife02059abbdce7920f1f408b71e9745d777fa770

2) Pass identity headers received in glanceclient to nova
Ifbef582aa4e64a2e7a46db43a9cc6cf8c3531dbd

3) Pass identity headers received by glance api to glance registry
Ie5f07ed6dfeaa8428de4f79c4d40d182328e6ab4

NOTE: since this is a change to a Dom0 plugin API, it requires the lock-step
upgrade of both the compute-manager and the dom0 plugin.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I6d5e3448d2c0acc392d18e0b88cec25cf313da5b

commit_message:
Skip secgroup invalid name/desc tests until bug 1161411 is fixed

There is an existing review which tries to deal with bug 1161411:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/34559/

Until there is consensus on how to fix this, skip the compute tests if
neutron is available.

Change-Id: I41bd2232ad4e489daaa8de3902d7e158f3e577bf

commit_message:
Add provision config for 'service_available'.

 * tempest.conf has a new section called 'service_available' that
   indicates the availability for testing of each service
   individually.  Previously only neutron availability was
   configurable.

Change-Id: I6967a76deb7314eb8770e655b6d5562c661183e3

Remove unused keystone params from neutron agents' config files

DHCP, L3 and Metadata agents' config files no longer need to
duplicate this info; it's available in neutron.conf

commit_message:
python WebOb dependency made unpinned.

keystone declares python-webob dependency as ==,
which is not a good way of defining dependency.
So to support latest dependencies, WebOb is unpinned in
requirements.txt

Fixes: bug #1180033
Change-Id: I73042cf88baf378c8564abb2394963866082977e

commit_message:
Cleanup mount points automatically.

Manually listing the mount points that need cleanup is not
maintainable and makes it hard to write elements that use bind
mounting to inject resources into the build environment.

Change-Id: I7c9ade444f4ebe42552f8e321f257a7ec0a674ef

commit_message:
Update QUANTUM_PLUGIN_CONFIG for N1K cisco plugin

when deploying n1k cisco plugin make sure to update the quantum_plugin_config
so the plugin is loaded appropriately. Since grizzly uses multi config,
only do this for n1k plugin which uses single config and let other plugin
use the default behavior.

Change-Id: I3a360e991c954570b729b547ef8b00d4eebd4a39

commit_message:
Fix router interface addition check.

 * The cli has changed its output to include the interface id,
   which breaks router interface addition.
 * Did I mention we need to stop parsing cli output and switch
   to fog?

Change-Id: I6711d6e10d3dd5b6173a0cf8fc617a35bb75cd10

commit_message:
Add support for multiple cinder endpoints

Before v1 and v2 were set to the same service_type, so you could only
have one set at a time. This assumes the catalog is setup for v1
service_type 'volume' and v2 service_type 'volumev2'.

For backwards compatibility, we will allow v2 to be setup with
service_type 'volume' for existing installations.

Change-Id: Ife6d2cdb12d894b84ea3b276767fb93d487355d5

commit_message:
python3: Fix traceback while running tests.

Fix:

TypeError: Unicode-objects must be encoded before hashing

while running tests. This is due to the fact in python3 hashlib.md5
works with bytes and we are passing unicode strings.

Change-Id: Iaf6cfb7d42f4559d1966a2c11faac3144a307da6
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Rework class inheritance for scenario tests

This commit reworks the class inheritance used by the scenario tests
to make is a bit simpler and similar to what is used for the api
tests. The scenario tests now inheret from the base test case directly
and client creation is handled directly instead of looping over the
client_attr_names list.

Change-Id: Id8bf2db3ec8f706ca466b86fa71df3ee2607fe88

commit_message:
use dev-requirements for global sync

This allows us to pass through an exact line from
dev-requirements.txt as valid, if it's not exactly valid we'll
revert to the base requirement. This is needed so that projects
can keep development requirements in their tree.

Redo an if statement to make E125 happy....

Change-Id: I50a1292c321b7092ca1c7aeee5068f0828ece7b0

Add support for service plugins to the migration framework

Implements blueprint migrations-for-service-plugins
Fixes bug 1209151

At the same time, as per my initial question, please let me know if you think it is worth checking the actual disk contents or not. commit_message:
scenario test involving glance, cinder and nova functionalities

this is a new scenario test which tries to address a typical use
case where an image is uploaded in glance, later cloned into a
persistent volume in cinder, snapshotted and finally reused for new
instances; there is no attempt to check the actual image contents as
that would require ssh access

Change-Id: I55f0e5fdfc5aba8eb6c8f427ab0e672bb7dcd715

[{'created': '2013-08-06 23:01:41.000000000', 'message': 'Add "total", "oldest" and "newest" to queue stats

This patch introduces three new queue stats in order to expose
a better user experience via control panels. Also included in
the changes is a bug fix for calculating timestamp differences,
as well as a refactoring of the way some MongoDB methods support
passing queue_id as a string vs. and ObjectId, in order to
reduce code duplication.

Note that there are several remaining stats identified in the
associated blueprint. This may be addressed in a future
patch.

Implements: blueprint extra-queue-stats
Change-Id: I31e48a581ccdd014ec97674af0c0dd43c808c42c

commit_message:
Add "total", "oldest" and "newest" to queue stats

This patch introduces three new queue stats in order to expose
a better user experience via control panels. Also included in
the changes is a bug fix for calculating timestamp differences,
as well as a renaming of 'queue' to 'queue_name' for consistency
within the MongoDB driver.

Note that there are several remaining stats identified in the
associated blueprint. This may be addressed in a future
patch.

Implements: blueprint extra-queue-stats
Change-Id: I31e48a581ccdd014ec97674af0c0dd43c808c42c

commit_message:
libvirt driver capable of generating device names

Implement the method from the base driver class to let libvirt
provide device names if the manager requests them.

This allows to boot an instance without having to care about
device names and delegating that task to the compute driver.

blueprint: improve-block-device-handling

Change-Id: I2b4f2ea6a4d2e4133e0ba12edabaa754744b8fa4

commit_message:
Update oslo-incubator requirements

The patch pulls in the latest versions of Oslo's modules being used by
Marconi. The main reason triggering this update is local.py not
depending on eventlet anymore.

commit_message:
feat(wsgi): claim creation returns 201

The API used to return 200, but 201 seems to be a better choice
for an action with modification.

Change-Id: I392d3e8fa821c7c1ace549187af4c6ca18457e09
Fixes: bug #1210301

commit_message:
feat(transport): place request size limit for JSON

To not deserialize over-sized requests with content body,
we also need transport-specific size restrictions.  They are
come before input validation, and are also configurable.

Change-Id: I06434431b3df9250c05472b4d91a53dfedb682d2

'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2013-06-14 09:28:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Point of information:

This makes python-pbr a run-time dependency.

With the currently existing Ubuntu packages this seems to lead to the following dependency chain:

 $ dpkg -I python-pbr_0.5.11-0ubuntu2_all.deb | grep Depends
 Depends: python (>= 2.7.1-0ubuntu2), python (<< 2.8), python-d2to1, python-setuptools, python- setuptools-git

this in turn has a dependency on git:

 $ dpkg -I python-setuptools-git_0.4.2-0ubuntu3_all.deb | grep Depends
 Depends: python2.7, python (>= 2.7.1-0ubuntu2), python (<< 2.8), python-setuptools, git

So, for now at least, this change would mean that installing glance would also require installing 'git'.

Monty is working on a solution for this with Chuck."}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-06-14 11:37:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2013-06-17 18:12:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Stuarts comment makes me nervous. I'm out of sync with packaging requirements, so I wonder if anyone could answer the following questions for me?

- Why are setup/install dependencies would be listed as runtime dependencies for a project? Is there not a distinction between these two types of dependencies?

- Is it just a packaging problem in ubuntu that build dependencies are leaking into regular dependencies? Or is that mandated by something glance is doing?"}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-06-17 22:14:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

Wrt this "Monty is working on a solution for this with Chuck" - is there a bug filed for it?'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2013-06-18 21:34:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Why are setup/install dependencies would be listed as runtime dependencies for a project? Is there not a distinction between these two types of dependencies?

pbr is both a setup and a runtime depend. It's used to get version information post install.

    Is it just a packaging problem in ubuntu that build dependencies are leaking into regular dependencies? Or is that mandated by something glance is doing?

It's not glance specific, and the big issue is setuptools_git right now. We have a replacement up for review for it, so that as a runtime depend, and therefore git as a runtime depend, should totally go away once we do."}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2013-06-25 17:47:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

commit_message:
Migrate to PBR for setup and version code.

Fixes bug 1179007

Also, sync with global requirements because we can't do it in two steps.

Change-Id: If1c687f874272b9d9569af9dd1e5cb4457308f5c

[{'created': '2013-08-01 02:44:29.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for API message localization

Using the lazy gettext functionality from oslo gettextutils,
it is possible to use the Accept-Language header to translate
an exception message to the user requested locale and return
that translation from the API.

Implements bp user-locale-api

Change-Id: I48de5e681827305eef60c7a77e8d3091f9d64be0
Co-authored-by: Mathew Odden <mrodden@us.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Add support for API message localization

Using the lazy gettext functionality from oslo gettextutils,
it is possible to use the Accept-Language header to translate
an exception message to the user requested locale and return
that translation from the API.

Implements bp user-locale-api

Change-Id: I48de5e681827305eef60c7a77e8d3091f9d64be0
Co-authored-by: Mathew Odden <mrodden@us.ibm.com>
Co-authored-by: Ben Nemec <openstack@nemebean.com>

[{'created': '2013-06-26 18:26:13.000000000', 'message': 'python3: Fix import compatibility

Python3 reorganized the standard library and moved several functions
to different modules. Six provides a consistent interface
to them through the fake six.moves module.

However, the urlparse, urllib2, etc modules have been combined
into one module which Six does not support so do it the old
fashioned way.

Change-Id: Ia4f28639c396609d0560b5de4f47d2a04fa0af52
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
python3: Fix import compatibility

Python3 reorganized the standard library and moved several functions
to different modules. Six provides a consistent interface
to them through the fake six.moves module.

However, the urlparse, urllib2, etc modules have been combined
into one module which Six does not support so do it the old
fashioned way.

This is covered upstream but not included in six by
https://bitbucket.org/gutworth/six/pull-request/5/create-sixmovesurllib

Change-Id: Ia4f28639c396609d0560b5de4f47d2a04fa0af52
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
s/alarm/alarm_id/ in alarm notification

During the review cycle for the alarm notifier, the notification payload
was changed from containing the entire alarm representation to just the
alarm UUID.

However, the field name remained as 'alarm' which could be confusing.

Hence, we change this to alarm_id.

Change-Id: I5d9409df92010c7c89ad1f108b074bbf8487bb90

commit_message:
Include previous state in alarm notification

We now provide both the current and previous alarm states
in the notification.

This allows differential logic to be applied by the webhook
implementation, for example depending on whether the previous
state was known or insufficient data.

It also allows the initial and subsequent notifications to be
distinguished for repeat_actions alarms, without resorting to
fragile string comparisons between 'Transition to ...' and
'Remaining as ...'.

Change-Id: I61294e98ddf504b3ab22e9b16ab718d64c27486f

commit_message:
Fix H102, H103 Apache 2.0 license hacking check error

Closes-Bug: #1209070

This commit addresses H102 and H103 hacking check.
  H102  Apache 2.0 license header not found
  H103  Header does not match Apache 2.0 License notice

Also ignores H233 hacking check in tox.ini.
  H233  Python 3.x incompatible use of print operator

Change-Id: I081964bf0b9e21614da2f146bd3ba8d28e211024

'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-07-29 16:00:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(8 inline comments)

This code needs to be rearranged a bit, but it's mostly OK.

To be honest, though, I don't think this is ambitious enough. At the end of this process we want HOT to be the native template format, not the 6-toed cousin of template formats, and we won't get there by continuing to munge strings and dictionaries internally.

Classes like Template used __getitem__ at the beginning because they replaced plain dictionaries that were being passed around, and in many places (particularly unit tests) dictionaries were still being passed to functions that read from Templates. Now that e.g. the Template class is used almost everywhere, we should be starting to treat it as an object and calling methods like t.parameter_schemata() to get the parameter schemata, instead of t['Parameters']. Then we can override methods to provide different behaviour between template formats instead of hacking strings. Then we start pushing the same design pattern down from the top-level Template to its constituent parts - in this particular case we really need a "ParameterSchema" class that knows how to interpret the schema, and then the check_*() methods can just be functions that operate on any schema object.

To quote myself from the mailing list when I originally proposed handling the HOT format inside heat-engine:

"[P]utting the code in the engine offers the prospect of a more incremental way of changing over: by gradually replacing code that directly manipulates the structure of the template data with programmatic interfaces to to it (e.g. instead of doing template['Parameters'] and getting a JSON tree back, call template.parameters() and get a Parameters object back)."
--- http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-May/009551.html'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-07-30 00:32:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I want to echo Zane's sentiments and try to state it in my own words too.

Replace t['Parameters'] with t.parameter_schemata() and gain a world of readability and consistency throughout the code. Replace 'Parameters' with 'parameters' and we start going cross eyed."}, {'account_id': 7761, 'date': '2013-07-30 01:12:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (2 inline comments)

commit_message:
HOT parameter validator part

Introduce new class ParamSchema to decouple parameter and its schema,
do validation in schema, for hot template, implement HotParamSchema as
it subclass.

Implements blueprint hot-parameters

Change-Id: I8720c62e41a1f182584c4518163d422784c23b37

commit_message:
Check host exists before evacuate

Before an evacuate is attempted, there is no checks in
place to see if the host exists. This
results in rpc call being made to non existent host.

This patch adds a simple check to both v2 and v3 extensions
to ensure that the compute service exists before we attempt
to evacuate.

Fixes bug 1208369

Change-Id: I07103ecb8310d8a891ee5fb21a1f8aa7427e0d78

commit_message:
Handle more Nova and Neutron events

This introduces a simpler matching system for event types that supports
wildcard. We use this to grab all Nova instances notifications and a bit
more Neutron events.

We also change the get_event_types to a property to simplify the code a
bit.

Change-Id: Ica133ff2e9348a5d2640f068251d034bbd8a4f43

commit_message:
Allow non-use of cfg.CONF in securemessage

If someone passes a ConfigOpts instance other than cfg.CONF, we need
to register the group and options with it.

Change-Id: I10908d5e29d8a871ae29a5d3fa3f415e487f23b8

The existing schema limits for meter.resource_metadata column to
5000 characters, which may not be enough for a large metadata
payload encoded as JSON.

in that column without worrying about overflowing.

commit_message:
Change meter.resource_metadata column type

The existing schema limits for meter.resource_metadata column to
5000 characters, which may not be enough for a large metadata
payload encoded as JSON.
Using a Text column will let us store an arbitrary amount of data
in that column without worrying about overflowing.

Closes-Bug: #1204638

Change-Id: I5eb1cdbb3d4770a8348682634a78ccb0f843c141

[{'created': '2013-08-08 21:25:10.000000000', 'message': '3PAR drivers creating incorrect comment data

The 3PAR volumes created from a shapshot had incorrect comment data
that gets added in the comment section of the volumes on the backend.
This patch fixes the display name and description by getting the correct
data when the volume is created. This patch also fixes the inconsistency
in how the keys (name vs. display_name) were used in the comments.

Change-Id: I61af8ceb08d862f2b9dea2d9bb44c803e0b75a10
Fixes: bug 1210245
'}]
commit_message:
3PAR drivers creating incorrect comment data

The 3PAR volumes created from a shapshot had incorrect comment data
that gets added in the comment section of the volumes on the backend.
This patch fixes the display name and description by getting the correct
data when the volume is created. This patch also fixes the inconsistency
in how the keys (name vs. display_name) were used in the comments.

Change-Id: I61af8ceb08d862f2b9dea2d9bb44c803e0b75a10
Fixes: bug 1210245

which we use to configure a per-project list of modules which we will

'}]
commit_message:
Add a per-transport allow_remote_exmods API

Currently we have a allowed_rpc_exception_modules configuration variable
which we use to configure a per-project list of modules which we will
allow exceptions to be instantiated from when deserializing remote
errors.

It makes no sense for this to be user configurable, instead the list of
modules should be set when you create a transport.

Closes-Bug: #1031719
Change-Id: Ib40e92cb920996ec5e8f63d6f2cbd88fd01a90f2

commit_message:
Expose RemoteError exception in the public API

If a remote endpoint raises an exception which the client is not allowed
to (or cannot) deserialize, then RPCClient.call() raises a RemoteError
exception instead.

Make this exception type part of the public API.

Change-Id: I70be0ab7d40af3224d93d6bd0522c1a82f6303c3

[{'created': '2013-08-07 08:30:38.000000000', 'message': 'Add API for expected endpoint exceptions

Review I4e7b19dc730342091fd70a717065741d56da4555 gives a lot of the
background here, but the idea is that some exceptions raised by an RPC
endpoint method do not indicate any sort of failure and should not be
logged by the server as an error.

The classic example of this is conductor's instance_get() method raising
InstanceNotFound. This is perfectly normal and should not be considered
an error.

The new API is a decorator which you can use with RPC endpoints methods
to indicate which exceptions are expected:

    @messaging.expected_exceptions(InstanceNotFound)
    def instance_get(self, context, instance_id):
        ...

but we also need to expose the ExpectedException type itself so that
direct "local" users of the endpoint class know what type will be used
to wrap expected exceptions. For example, Nova has an ExceptionHelper
class which unwraps the original exception from an ExpectedException and
re-raises it.

I've changed from client_exceptions() and ClientException to make it
more clear it's intent. I felt that the "client" naming gave the
impression it was intended for use on the client side.

Change-Id: Ieec4600bd6b70cf31ac7925a98a517b84acada4d

commit_message:
Add API for expected endpoint exceptions

Review I4e7b19dc730342091fd70a717065741d56da4555 gives a lot of the
background here, but the idea is that some exceptions raised by an RPC
endpoint method do not indicate any sort of failure and should not be
logged by the server as an error.

The classic example of this is conductor's instance_get() method raising
InstanceNotFound. This is perfectly normal and should not be considered
an error.

The new API is a decorator which you can use with RPC endpoints methods
to indicate which exceptions are expected:

    @messaging.expected_exceptions(InstanceNotFound)
    def instance_get(self, context, instance_id):
        ...

but we also need to expose the ExpectedException type itself so that
direct "local" users of the endpoint class know what type will be used
to wrap expected exceptions. For example, Nova has an ExceptionHelper
class which unwraps the original exception from an ExpectedException and
re-raises it.

I've changed from client_exceptions() and ClientException to make it
more clear it's intent. I felt that the "client" naming gave the
impression it was intended for use on the client side.

Change-Id: Ieec4600bd6b70cf31ac7925a98a517b84acada4d

@Marc: I'm sorry but for that very same reason, I'm -1 this. I've proposed it in the agenda for the next QA meeting and added a link to the review so other people can read what that is about before the meeting.

My initial suggestion for saurabh to merge the action tests into a single class was based on the idea that repeating all those actions, in a sequence, concurrently, on a number of servers, was the actual stress case. If we keep instead all the actions in a separate class/file, what is that we are testing? Also, keeping the tests in different files requires thread_num*actions_num instances to be spawn, which would just slow down things with no real benefits as we do have a server_create_destroy stress test already for that.

I agree with you that the code is perfect though but we need to figure what is that we want/need to stress.

commit_message:
Add a driver method specifically for sending notifications

Notifications are an unusual case in that we need users to manually opt
in to new incompatible message formats by editing configuration because
there may be external consumers expecting the old format.

Add a send_notification() method to the driver interface and add a
format version paramater to the method, to make it clear that this
version selection is specifically for notifications.

In the case of the rabbit/qpid drivers, the 2.0 format is where we added
the message envelope.

Change-Id: Ib4925c308b1252503749962aa16f043281f2b429

commit_message:
Enforce target preconditions outside of drivers

The target preconditions (e.g. you need at least a topic to send) are
the same for all drivers, so enforce them before we ever call into a
driver.

Change-Id: Ic4e9bd94bd9f060ec0662d2bb778c699903dddc4

Add comments to ReplyWaiter.wait()

This method is fairly gnarly, so break my usual preference to make the
intent clear from the code and instead include detailed comments in the
method.

if Store has incorrect configuration in glance-api.conf,
configure_add() function in Store will raise exception.BadStoreConfiguration,
which cause glance-api start failed and raise UnicodeEncodeError like this
"UnicodeEncodeError: 'ascii' codec can't encode characters in position 0-7: ordinal not in range(128)"

Fixes Bug 1206326

Change-Id: I89934a7b063b44da8be3db475b99dffa685d247a
'}]
commit_message:
fix UnicodeEncodeError raised in glance/store/base.py when system locale is non-ascii

if Store has incorrect configuration in glance-api.conf,
configure_add() function in Store will raise exception.BadStoreConfiguration,
which cause glance-api start failed and raise UnicodeEncodeError like this
"UnicodeEncodeError: 'ascii' codec can't encode characters in position 0-7: ordinal not in range(128)"

Fixes Bug 1206326

Change-Id: I89934a7b063b44da8be3db475b99dffa685d247a

commit_message:
Started work on cinder stress test

This is a WIP patch to migrate my
custom standalone cinder stress test
into tempest stress

Stress loop:
volume creation
snapshot creation
snapshot deletion
volume deletion

Change-Id: I58299d70ed928218c236ac34291fb2eb1c9a6030

commit_message:
Fix display of volume/snapshot choices for BfV

- Show ID for None display name in boot from volume
  Fixes LP Bug #1199206

- Use an unicode string, fixes display of translations
  Fixes LP Bug #1199837

Change-Id: I192e299bdefbcc64ab3288f0c1326a58604e8bc0

Better logging to debug why Auth token fails.

Need a debug level log to help identify the exact request and response
for failed authentication of the token.

commit_message:
Handle disk constraint failures during live migration

Reports from Nova-Compute are reported back as RemoteError
due to the RPC calls. Treat any RPC RemoteError as an
invalid host and continue scheduling.

Fixes LP Bug #1199885

Change-Id: I586d34fa615279233521177044546475476f8f40

I am not convinced that it makes sense to change every driver copy_volume_to_image() when only one driver actually makes use of the new arg. Also, if it is not safe for this operation to occur when the volume is in use perhaps the volume manager should disallow it."}, {'account_id': 6939, 'date': '2013-07-06 00:32:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The manager allow you to copy_vol_to_img on an in_use volume ONLY when a force Argument pass in with the request.

But the problem is that in the original code,driver has no way to learn whether the volume is in_use when they try to copy that volume,this patch give them such info

I am not the expert for every backend so I cannot make use of the in_use arg in every driver, so I would like to leave the arg there,waiting for the backend expert to do so.
with such in_use info ,the driver can do better, say for RBD, it snap the volume first and then copy on the snapshot.Then it is safe for RBD to do a copy_to_img even the RBD is in use.
For some backend that they have no way to do so and they decide to disallow copying an in_use volume,they can do so with the in_use arg passed in'}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2013-07-09 15:24:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(2 inline comments)

Copying an in-use volume to an image is a pretty insane thing to do... commit_message:
Add a force flag for copy_volume_to_image

Add an force flag and pass to the driver when calling copy_volume_to_image,
to tell them whether the volume is currently in use,so they can come up with
something more precious for better consistency.

fixed bug 1194976

Change-Id: I971eb874bf23dd403caa1ab620903d7b776605ba

commit_message:
Ignore stmf target must be offline exception

Patch to ignore

"NexentaJSONException: : Unable to add member to targetgroup:
    stmfadm: STMF target must be offline"

This error happens when targetgroup is already configured and busy.

fixed bug 1209305

Change-Id: I275dcf465934c99d30f85932fe72e8b1818ef870

I agree a 400 is more sensible here.
Thanks for addressing all my questions in the commit message.

Technical it is considered ok to change a response code and make it more accurtate. I would translate this to changing a 500 (ie: the server raises a random exception) to a 400 (the server exception is mapped to a client error).

One thing that I consider also acceptable however, is fixing error response codes which were wrong in the first place, and this is the case of this patch.
Of course, when people start building scripts and other client tools and wrong response codes it becomes harder to replace the error, but this is a remote corner case, so we should not be worried about it.'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2013-08-08 23:17:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

Nova is trying to do a better job of mapping Neutron exceptions and
change I4c087684ef77988e5f463d7f2f50fc2a04f37db0 is trying to map 409 to
the proper nova exception. In looking at what raises a 409 exception in
Neutron, the SubnetMismatchForPort exception seemed like a candidate for
changing from Conflict (409) to BadRequest (400) to ease that mapping.

Note that the only thing currently using this exception is the L3 router
extension when removing a router interface and the 400 response code is
already listed in the API docs as a possible response code:

http://docs.openstack.org/api/openstack-network/2.0/content/router_remove_interface.html

Also note that it's generally OK to change APIs for a more accurate
response code:

commit_message:
Make SubnetMismatchForPort extend BadRequest rather than Conflict

Nova is trying to do a better job of mapping Neutron exceptions and
change I4c087684ef77988e5f463d7f2f50fc2a04f37db0 is trying to map 409 to
the proper nova exception. In looking at what raises a 409 exception in
Neutron, the SubnetMismatchForPort exception seemed like a candidate for
changing from Conflict (409) to BadRequest (400) to ease that mapping.

Note that the only thing currently using this exception is the L3 router
extension when removing a router interface and the 400 response code is
already listed in the API docs as a possible response code:

http://docs.openstack.org/api/openstack-network/2.0/content/router_remove_interface.html

Also note that it's generally OK to change APIs for a more accurate
response code:

commit_message:
Fix heat event list sorted order incorrect

The order is correct already if python heat client does not recorder
it. Add option to make print_list not to reorder possible, and call it
in do_event_list.

Change-Id: I3f0990aff27df39371c583d5aae3edd106542ad1
Fixes: bug #1209506

commit_message:
First attempt to integrate Paul's HSM plugin into Barbican.

Initial mods to change the plugin interface a little bit, and to introduce
a new 'kek_data' table to house key encryption key (KEK) metadata used for
encryption/decryption. This new table will house per-tenant metadata.

Change-Id: I87cd0d4516fa19209be94cacdb79ac4b7eb740df

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-02 10:29:51.000000000', 'message': 'misleading source filename in error message

when ./stack.sh encounters error, the output may look like this:
[ERROR] ./stack.sh:698 nova-api did not start

The source filename is wrong. Actually, it should be like this:
[ERROR] /<path_of_devstack>/lib/nova:698 nova-api did not start

stack.sh uses bash as interpreter, which define "Shell Variables"
BASH_SOURCE:
    An array variable whose members are the source filenames where
    the corresponding shell function names  in  the  FUNCNAME  array
    variable  are  defined.   The  shell  function
    ${FUNCNAME[$i]}  is  defined  in  the  file ${BASH_SOURCE[$i]}
    and called from ${BASH_SOURCE[$i+1]}.

The function "err" is called by function "die" ( and "err_if_not_set",
and "err_if_not_set" is not used at all). ${BASH_SOURCE[2]} will
ignore the deepest two call entries, which corresponding to the shell
functions: "err" and "die".

In one sentence, this change will print the source filename where the
function is defined and exits via function "die".

Fixes bug #1207658

Change-Id: I2aa6642c5cf4cfe781afe278b3dec3e7cba277fa
'}]
commit_message:
misleading source filename in error message

when ./stack.sh encounters error, the output may look like this:
[ERROR] ./stack.sh:698 nova-api did not start

The source filename is wrong. Actually, it should be like this:
[ERROR] /<path_of_devstack>/lib/nova:698 nova-api did not start

stack.sh uses bash as interpreter, which define "Shell Variables"
BASH_SOURCE:
    An array variable whose members are the source filenames where
    the corresponding shell function names  in  the  FUNCNAME  array
    variable  are  defined.   The  shell  function
    ${FUNCNAME[$i]}  is  defined  in  the  file ${BASH_SOURCE[$i]}
    and called from ${BASH_SOURCE[$i+1]}.

The function "err" is called by function "die" ( and "err_if_not_set",
and "err_if_not_set" is not used at all). ${BASH_SOURCE[2]} will
ignore the deepest two call entries, which corresponding to the shell
functions: "err" and "die".

In one sentence, this change will print the source filename where the
function is defined and exits via function "die".

Fixes bug #1207658

Change-Id: I2aa6642c5cf4cfe781afe278b3dec3e7cba277fa

Commit dce64683291ba2cdb5e6617e01ccc2909254acb4 added the want_objects
flag to compute_api.get to the _restore function for the V3 version
of deferred delete and the _force_delete function for the V2 version.

This changeset makes it consistent so the want_objects flag is
passed to both. The unittests are also updated accordingly. The inconsistency
was found by the integrated test_servers test which is not yet merged
for the V3 API.

Change-Id: I797f8da855fda8df823e9093cb51ef5da6bdcb0f
'}]
commit_message:
Fix deferred delete use of objects

Commit dce64683291ba2cdb5e6617e01ccc2909254acb4 added the want_objects
flag to compute_api.get to the _restore function for the V3 version
of deferred delete and the _force_delete function for the V2 version.

This changeset makes it consistent so the want_objects flag is
passed to both. The unittests are also updated accordingly. The inconsistency
was found by the integrated test_servers test which is not yet merged
for the V3 API.

Change-Id: I797f8da855fda8df823e9093cb51ef5da6bdcb0f

commit_message:
Fixed merge code populating properties from yaml.

Fixed merge code populating properties from yaml files which was
setting only Type attribute for certain attribues related to Image
For example, default value for notcomputeImage is populated properly
in overcloud.yaml

Fixes bug #1202884

Change-Id: I9ea270dd19e9ebdb997be5d07b04ee2df28e3721

commit_message:
Adds rpc package to openstack-common.conf

The modules glance/openstack/common/notifier/rpc_notifier.py and
glance/openstack/common/notifier/rpc_notifier2.py requires
the rpc package from oslo.  Added rpc to openstack-common.conf

Fixes bug #1201695

Change-Id: Ie64d5e18b5b1a1221193fba9f8f84e954b4baf54

commit_message:
Externalize error messages in the API

This patch does more internationalization for the REST API error
messages that don't currently have it to take advantage of the new
support added by bp user-locale-api to show error messages in the locale
requested by the user through the Accept-Language HTTP header.

Partially implements bp user-locale-api

Change-Id: I92780b42c125a91ab4916b7a31e4b71d306a89a1

commit_message:
Enhance object inheritance

Objects could only inherit fields from the NovaObject base class.  This
patch fixes this so that any object subclassed from another object will
inherit all fields.

Related to blueprint unified-object-model

Change-Id: Iaf511be490a44d357b4f527d37a64f3794c60afe

Fixes Opt types in glance/notifier/notify_kombu.py

Changed rabbit_retry_backoff and rabbit_retry_max_backoff to IntOpt.

Fixes bug #1201697

Yep, just wanted to get them posted somewhere as some people on my team needed them for some other work they were doing and I figured these would eventually be needed.'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2013-08-08 12:52:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm thinking we may want to keep the quantum stuff in the puppet-nova module in addition to adding new neutron stuff.

There may be a couple exceptions where we need to change/remove the existing quantum configuration stuff because of how it is written. For example in api.pp we may want to make the following change:

-      'DEFAULT/service_quantum_metadata_proxy': value => false;
+      'DEFAULT/service_quantum_metadata_proxy': value => absent;

This is because Nova using neutron or quantum options (quantum opts are now marked as deprecated).

Since Nova's default for service_quantum_metadata_proxy is False there is no need to set it anyway.

----

Our goal is to support Havana plus Grizzly with the latest puppet-nova modules so I think we'll have to go this route."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2013-08-08 13:48:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

I've tested both puppet-quantum & puppet-neutron with rename patches.

I've used Debian packages that we build.

Everything is working.
